{"title_page": "Glycerine (song)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2014}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Glycerine\n| cover      = bush_glycerine.png\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Bush (British band)|Bush]]\n| album      = [[Sixteen Stone]]\n| B-side     = Solomon's Bones , Alien [LP Version]\n| released   = {{start date|df=yes|1995|11|14}}\n| format     = [[CD single|CD]], [[Gramophone record|7\"]]\n| recorded   = January 1994\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n* [[Alternative rock]]<ref>[https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2007/05/the-ultimate-nineties-alt-rock-playlist/40279/ The Ultimate Nineties Alt-Rock Playlist]<br/> [[The Atlantic]]. Retrieved 2016-02-22</ref>\n* [[post-grunge]]<ref>https://www.spin.com/2014/08/100-best-alternative-rock-songs-1994-alt/1dgel6g25ka9o0g4ic4e6ogoogeo/</ref> \n|}}\n| label      = {{flatlist|\n*[[Trauma Records|Trauma]]\n*[[Interscope Records|Interscope]]\n*[[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n}}\n| writer     = [[Gavin Rossdale]]\n| producer   = {{flatlist|\n*[[Clive Langer]]\n*[[Alan Winstanley]]\n*Bush\n}}\n| prev_title = [[Comedown (song)|Comedown]]\n| prev_year  = 1995\n| next_title = [[Machinehead (song)|Machinehead]]\n| next_year  = 1996\n}}\n\n\"'''Glycerine'''\" is a song by English band [[Bush (band)|Bush]]. It was released on 14 November 1995 as the fourth single from their debut album, ''[[Sixteen Stone]]''.\n\n==Composition==\n[[Gavin Rossdale]] wrote the song about his then-girlfriend, model Jasmine Lewis. He wrote it in his [[London]] flat, feeling that there was an ancient, mystical element to the song as it was coming together. He told ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' in 2017 that \"I was like a conduit. Something about it was bigger than anything we were doing.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.songfacts.com/facts/bush/glycerine|title=Glycerine by Bush |website= Songfacts|date= |accessdate=January 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe song is in the key of [[F major]]. The [[chord progression]] is F maj \u2013 C maj \u2013 D min \u2013 B{{music|flat}} maj throughout the [[Verse (music)|verse]] with various ornamental embellishments [[diatonic]] to the key of F major, including the [[Bridge (music)|bridge]] which cycles between the I (F major), V (C major), IV (B{{music|flat}} major), and V chord in F Major. The refrain towards the end hangs on the vi (D minor) \u2013 IV (B{{music|flat}} major) before returning to the recurring progression for the last verse.\n\nThe single includes a previously unreleased B-side, \"Solomon's Bones\", which was recorded on 7 November 1995 at River Studios, London and engineered by Joel Monger.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/Bush-Glycerine/release/3318361|title=Bush \u2013 Glycerine|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\nThe music video for \"Glycerine\" was notable for being shot in a very short time period when the band was on tour in the United States. The video was shot so quickly because the band's visas had expired. Though simple and unadorned, the video was highly acclaimed and won several awards, including the [[MTV Video Music Award - Viewer's Choice]] as well nominated for [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Alternative Video|Best Alternative Video]] at the 1996 [[MTV Video Music Awards]]. The music video was directed by [[Kevin Kerslake]] and shot in Atlanta, Georgia on 2 October 1995.<ref>\n{{cite web\n |url         = http://onesecondbush.com/bush/media/videos/\n |title       = Archived copy\n |accessdate  = 2012-03-04\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20120220231659/http://onesecondbush.com/bush/media/videos\n |archivedate = 20 February 2012\n |df          = dmy\n}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n# \"Glycerine\"\n# \"Solomon's Bones\"\n# \"Alien\" [LP Version]\n\n==Commercial performance==\nFollowing the album's third single, \"[[Comedown (song)|Comedown]]\", \"Glycerine\" shared equal success. Like \"Comedown\", it reached number one on the [[Alternative Songs|Modern Rock Tracks]] chart for two weeks, in December 1995. It is also the band's biggest pop hit to date, peaking at number 28 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] on 24 February 1996.<ref name=\"BillboardHot100\">{{cite web|title=Bush \u2013 Chart history \u2013 Billboard|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/1486092/Bush/chart?f=379|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=18 December 2016}}</ref> The song won the [[Viewer's Choice (MTV)|Viewer's Choice Award]] at the 1996 [[MTV Music Video Awards]]. The song was voted number 5 on the Australian annual music poll [[Triple J Hottest 100]] in [[Triple J Hottest 100, 1996|1996]].\n\n==Chart positions==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (1995\u201396)\n!Peak<br/>Position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Australia|5|artist=Bush|song=Glycerine}}\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Canada Top Singles ([[RPM (magazine)|RPM]])\n|align=\"center\"|38\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Canada [[Canadian Rock/Alternative chart|Alternative 30]] ([[RPM (magazine)|RPM]])\n|align=\"center\"|3\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch100|41|artist=Bush|song=Glycerine}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|New Zealand|31|artist=Bush|song=Glycerine}}\n|-\n|{{singlechart|Billboardhot100|28|artist=Bush|artistid=1486092|accessdate=9 April 2015}}\n|-\n|{{singlechart|Billboardalternativesongs|1|artist=Bush|artistid=1486092|accessdate=9 April 2015}}\n|-\n|{{singlechart|Billboardmainstreamrock|4|artist=Bush|artistid=1486092|accessdate=3 April 2015}}\n|-\n|{{singlechart|Billboardpopsongs|28|artist=Bush|artistid=1486092|accessdate=3 April 2015}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Live version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Glycerine (Live)\n| cover      = Bush Glycerine ft. Gwen Stefani.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Bush (band)|Bush]] featuring [[Gwen Stefani]]\n| album      =\n| released   = {{start date|df=yes|2012|12|13}}\n| format     = [[Digital distribution|Digital download]]\n| recorded   = 8 December 2012\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Post-grunge]]<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web | url=http://www.stylusmagazine.com/articles/staff_top_10/top-ten-mediocre-post-grunge-alternative-bands.htm | title=Top Ten Mediocre Post-Grunge / Alternative Bands | work=[[Stylus Magazine]] | accessdate=30 July 2015 | author=Unterberger, Andrew}}</ref>\n| length     = 4:38\n| label      = Zuma Rock\n| writer     = [[Gavin Rossdale]]\n| producer   =\n| chronology = [[Bush (band)|Bush]]\n| prev_title = [[Baby Come Home (Bush song)|Baby Come Home]]\n| prev_year  = 2012\n| next_title = [[The Only Way Out (Bush song)|The Only Way Out]]\n| next_year  = 2014\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[Gwen Stefani]]\n | type       = single\n | prev_title = [[Early Winter]]\n | prev_year  = 2008\n | title      = Glycerine\n | year       = 2012\n | next_title = [[Baby Don't Lie]]\n | next_year  = 2014\n}}\n}}\n\nBush performed a new version of \"Glycerine\" at [[KROQ Almost Acoustic Christmas]] on 8 December 2012, which featured a surprise appearance from American singer and songwriter, and Gavin Rossdale's then-wife [[Gwen Stefani]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/earshot/gwen-stefani-glycerine-duet-husband-gavin-rossdale-itunes-406025| title=Gwen Stefani's 'Glycerine' Duet with Husband Gavin Rossdale Released on iTunes| work=The Hollywood Reporter | accessdate=23 September 2016|date=20 December 2012| author=Nicole Powell}}</ref> The single was never released on an album, as both Stefani and Bush were not working on any new material.\n\n=== Chart performance ===\nAfter its release, the live version received moderate success in the [[United States]]. On the ''Billboard'' Alternative Digital Singles chart, \"Glycerine\" peaked at number 16, whereas on the [[Rock Digital Singles|''Billboard'' Rock Digital Singles]], it peaked at number 22.\n\n=== Charts ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!Chart (2013)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| US Alternative Digital Singles ([[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']])<ref>{{cite web|title=Chart Search|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/search/charts?page=11&f[0]=ts_chart_artistname%3AGwen%20stefani&f[1]=ss_bb_type%3Achart_item&type=2&artist=Gwen%20stefani|publisher=[[Billboard charts|Billboard]] [[Rock Digital Songs]] for Gwen Stefani|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref>\n| 16\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardrocksongs|38|artist=Bush|rowheader=true|accessdate=26 December 2015}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| US [[Rock Digital Songs]] ([[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']])<ref>{{cite web|title=Chart Search|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/search/charts?f[0]=ts_chart_artistname%3AGwen%20Stefani&f[1]=ss_bb_type%3Achart_item&type=2&artist=Gwen%20Stefani|publisher=[[Billboard charts|Billboard]] [[Rock Digital Songs]] for Gwen Stefani|accessdate=26 December 2015}}</ref>\n| 22\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{youtube|hOllF3TgAsM|\"Glycerine\" Official music video}}\n* {{MetroLyrics song|bush|glycerine}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Bush}}\n{{Gwen Stefani songs}}\n\n[[Category:1995 singles]]\n[[Category:1990s ballads]]\n[[Category:Billboard Alternative Songs number-one singles]]\n[[Category:British alternative rock songs]]\n[[Category:Bush (British band) songs]]\n[[Category:Gwen Stefani songs]]\n[[Category:Music videos directed by Kevin Kerslake]]\n[[Category:Rock ballads]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Clive Langer]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Alan Winstanley]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Gavin Rossdale]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2014}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Glycerine\n| cover      = bush_glycerine.png\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Bush (British band)|Bush]]\n| album      = [[Sixteen Stone]]\n| B-side     = Solomon's Bones , Alien [LP Version]\n| released   = {{start date|df=yes|1995|1