{"title_page": "Confucius Institute", "text_new": "{{short description|Chinese government education, propaganda, and advocacy program promoting Mandarin Chinese and Chinese culture with a global focus}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| name = Confucius Institute\n| logo =  Confucious Institute logo.svg\n| logo_size = 150px\n| type = Cultural promotion organization\n| founded_date = {{start date and age|2004}}\n| location = 129 Deshengmen Outer Street, [[Xicheng District]], [[Beijing]]\n| key_people =\n| area_served = Worldwide\n| focus = [[Chinese culture]], [[Chinese language]]\n| method = Education and Advocacy\n| revenue =\n| endowment =\n| num_volunteers =\n| num_employees =\n| num_members =\n| owner = [[Ministry of Education of the People's Republic of China]]\n| Non-profit_slogan =\n| homepage = {{url|http://www.hanban.org/}}\n| dissolved =\n| footnotes =\n}}\n{{Chinese|s=\u5b54\u5b50\u5b66\u9662|t=\u5b54\u5b50\u5b78\u9662|p=K\u01d2ngz\u01d0 Xu\u00e9yu\u00e0n}}\n\n[[File:ICB-facade.JPG|thumb|Confucius Institute of [[Brittany (administrative region)|Brittany]] in [[Rennes]], France]]\n[[File:SenecaConfuciusInstitute2.jpg|thumb|A Confucius Institute at [[Seneca College]] in [[Toronto]], [[Canada]]]]\n\n'''Confucius Institute''' ({{zh|s = {{linktext|\u5b54\u5b50\u5b66\u9662}}|p = K\u01d2ngz\u01d0 Xu\u00e9yu\u00e0n}}) is a  public [[education]]al organization under the [[Ministry of Education of the People's Republic of China]],<ref name=ChinaU/> whose stated aim is to promote Chinese language and [[Culture of China|culture]], support local [[TCFL|Chinese teaching]] internationally, and facilitate cultural exchanges.<ref>{{cite news|last=Penn|first=Brierley|title=China Business:A broader education|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/china-business-2013/news/article.cfm?c_id=1503331&objectid=11238085|work=The New Zealand Herald|accessdate=21 April 2014|date=2014-04-15}}</ref><ref name=mattis>{{cite web|last=Mattis|first=Peter|title=Reexamining the Confucian Institutes|url=http://thediplomat.com/2012/08/reexamining-the-confucian-institutes/|work=The Diplomat|accessdate=21 April 2014|date=2 August 2012}}</ref> The organization has been criticized due to concerns of rising Chinese influences in the countries in which it operates.<ref>[http://www.economist.com/node/14678507 A message from Confucius; New ways of projecting soft power], ''The Economist'', 22 October 2009.</ref>\n\nThe Confucius Institute program began in 2004 and is overseen by [[Hanban]] (officially the Office of Chinese Language Council International). The institutes operate in co-operation with local affiliate colleges and universities around the world, and financing is shared between Hanban and the host institutions. The related Confucius Classroom program partners with local secondary schools or school districts to provide teachers and instructional materials.<ref>{{cite web|title=Introduction to the Confucius Institutes|url=http://college.chinese.cn/en/article/2009-08/29/content_22308.htm|accessdate=2 July 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707081524/http://college.chinese.cn/en/article/2009-08/29/content_22308.htm|archivedate=7 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author1=Jianguo Chen |author2=Chuang Wang |author3=Jinfa Cai |title=Teaching and learning Chinese: issues and perspectives|year=2010|publisher=IAP|pages=xix|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pGURhDOkdxEC&pg=PR19|isbn=9781617350641 }}</ref>\n\nChina has compared Confucius Institutes to language and culture promotion organizations such as Portugal's [[Instituto Cam\u00f5es]], Britain's [[British Council]], France's [[Alliance Fran\u00e7aise]], Italy's [[Societ\u00e0 Dante Alighieri]], Spain's [[Instituto Cervantes]] and Germany's [[Goethe-Institut]]\u2014several of them named for an iconic cultural figure identified with that country, as Confucius is identified with China.<ref name=20110220smh>Justin Norrie (2011), [http://www.smh.com.au/national/education/confucius-says-schools-in-but-dont-mention-democracy-20110219-1b09x.html Confucius says school's in, but don't mention democracy], ''The Sydney Morning Herald'', 20 February 2011.</ref> However, unlike these organizations, many Confucius Institutes operate directly on university campuses, thus giving rise to unique concerns related to academic freedom and political influence.<ref name=ChinaU/>\n\n==History==\nThe first Confucius Institute (CI) opened on 21 November 2004 in [[Seoul]], South Korea, after establishing a pilot institute in [[Tashkent]], Uzbekistan in June 2004. The CI in South Korea is no longer active. The second Confucius Institute was opened on the campus of the [[University of Maryland, College Park]], also in November 2004.<ref>[http://globalmaryland.umd.edu/offices/confucius-institute-maryland/frequently-asked-questions FAQ: When was CIM established?]</ref> Hundreds more have opened since in dozens of countries around the world, with the highest concentration of Institutes in the United States, Japan, and South Korea.<ref>{{cite book|last=Simon|first=Tay|title=Asia Alone: The Dangerous Post-Crisis Divide from America|year=2010|publisher=John Wiley and Sons|pages=42|url=https://books.google.com/?id=H-O-wYKRyGcC&pg=PA42#v=onepage&f=false|isbn=9780470826201}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2007, the first research-based Confucius Institute opened in [[Waseda University]] in Japan. In partnership with [[Peking University]], the program promotes research activities of graduate students studying Chinese.<ref>{{cite web|title=Signing of Waseda University Confucius Institute Agreement Established as the first Research Confucius Institute in collaboration with Peking University|url=http://www.waseda.jp/eng/news07/070412e.html|publisher=Waseda University|accessdate=11 July 2011}}</ref> \n\nAs of 2019, there are 530 Confucius Institutes in dozens of countries on six continents.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://english.hanban.org/node_10971.htm|title=HanBan-Confucius Institute/ClassRoom-About\u00a0Confucius Institute/ClassRoom|website=english.hanban.org|access-date=2019-10-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Confucius Institutes Worldwide|url=http://www.confucius.ucla.edu/about-us/confucius-institutes-worldwide|publisher=UCLA Confucious Institute|accessdate=11 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://confuciusinstitute.unl.edu/institutes.shtml | title=Confucius Institutes Around the Globe &#124; Confucius Institute &#124; Nebraska}}</ref> The Ministry of Education estimates that 100 million people overseas may be learning Chinese by 2010 and the program is expanding rapidly in order to keep up.<ref>[http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2007-12/06/content_7212089.htm China to host second Confucius Institute Conference], Xinhua, 6 December 2007.</ref> \n\nHanban aims to establish 1,000 Confucius Institutes by 2020.<ref>[http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2006-10/02/content_5521722.htm Confucius Institute: promoting language, culture and friendliness] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021071750/http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2006-10/02/content_5521722.htm |date=21 October 2012 }}, Xinhua, 2 October 2006.</ref>\n\n==Name==\nThe Confucius Institute is named after the noted Chinese philosopher [[Confucius]] (551\u2013479 BC). Throughout the 20th century, [[Communist Party of China]] (CPC) leaders criticized and denounced Confucius as the personification of China's \"feudal\" traditions, with [[Chen Duxiu#Anti-Confucianism|anti-Confucianism]] ranging from the 1912 [[New Culture Movement]] to the 1973 [[Criticize Lin, Criticize Confucius]] campaign during the [[Cultural Revolution]].<ref>Starr (2009), p. 68.</ref> However, in recent decades, interest in pre-modern Chinese culture has grown in the country, and Confucius in particular has seen a resurgence in popularity.<ref>{{cite news|last=Melvin|first=Sheila|title=Yu Dan and China's Return to Confucius|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/08/29/arts/29iht-melvin.1.7298367.html|accessdate=2 July 2011|newspaper=The New York Times|date=29 August 2007}}</ref> Outside of China, Confucius is a generally recognizable symbol of [[Chinese culture]], removed from the negative associations of other prominent Chinese figures such as chairman [[Mao Zedong]].<ref>{{cite news|title=China's Confucius Institutes Rectification of statues|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/asiaview/2011/01/china\u2019s_confucius_institutes?page=1|accessdate=2 July 2011|newspaper=The Economist|date=20 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n\"Confucius Institute\" is a trademarked [[brand|brand name]], which according to a spokesman for the organisation, \"Those who enjoy more brand names will enjoy higher popularity, reputation, more social influence, and will therefore be able to generate more support from local communities.\"<ref>Starr (2009), p. 69.</ref> A 2011 crackdown protected \"Confucius Institute\" from [[Trademark#Registration|preregistration]] infringement in Costa Rica.<ref>Zhou Wenting, [http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/cndy/2011-07/29/content_13006180.htm Trademark infringement continues despite crackdown], ''China Daily'' 29 July 2011.</ref>\n\nA ''[[The China Post|China Post]]'' article reported in 2014 that \"Certainly, China would have made little headway if it had named these Mao Institutes, or even Deng Xiaoping Institutes. But by borrowing the name Confucius, it created a brand that was instantly recognized as a symbol of Chinese culture, radically different from the image of the Communist Party.\"<ref name=\"World should watch for Confucius\">[http://www.chinapost.com.tw/commentary/the-china-post/frank-ching/2014/10/01/418395/World-should.htm World should watch for Confucius], ''China Post'', 1 October 2014</ref>\n\nKerry Brown, Professor of Chinese Politics at the [[University of Sydney]], notes the irony that the CPC now lionizing Confucius had vilified him just four decades previously for his association with patriarchal, hierarchical, and conservative values.<ref>Kerry Brown, [http://www.scmp.com/comment/insight-opinion/article/1523308/case-eliminating-confucius-chinas-confucius-institutes The case for eliminating Confucius from China's Confucius Institutes], South China Morning Post, 2 June 2014.</ref>\n\n==Purpose==\n[[File:Signing ceremony (6943869420).jpg|thumb|262x262px|[[United Kingdom|British]] [[Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs|Foreign Secretary]] [[William Hague]] and Li Changchun at a signing ceremony in [[London]], 17 April 2012, for the agreement between Confucius Institute of China and [[Bangor University]] on the establishment of Confucius Institute at Bangor University, [[United Kingdom]]. The agreement was signed by John Hughes, [[Vice-Chancellor]] of Bangor University, and Xu Lin, Director of the Confucius Institute.]]\nConfucius Institutes (CIs) promote and teach Chinese culture and language around the world. CIs develop Chinese language courses, train teachers, hold the [[Hanyu Shuiping Kaoshi|HSK]] Examination (Chinese proficiency test), host cultural and artistic presentations, and provide information about contemporary China.<ref>{{cite web|title=About Us|url=http://about.chinese.cn/en/node_4221.htm|publisher=Confucius Institute|accessdate=3 July 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110811021842/http://about.chinese.cn/en/node_4221.htm|archivedate=11 August 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The director of the CI program, [[Xu Lin (Hanban)|Xu Lin]], stated that CIs were started to cater to the sudden uptick in interest of the Chinese language around the world. They also provide Chinese language teaching staff from Mainland China. As of 2011, there were 200 such teachers working in the United States.<ref>{{cite book|title=Teaching and Learning Chinese in Global Contexts|year=2011|publisher=Continuum International Publishing Group|url=https://books.google.com/?id=4q53niG5MLIC&pg=PA2#v=onepage&f=false|author1=Linda Tsung |author2=Ken Cruickshank |page=151|isbn=9781441100399}}</ref>\n\n==Political goals==\nThe Confucius Institute also has non-academic goals. [[Li Changchun]], the 5th-highest-ranking member of the [[Politburo Standing Committee of the Communist Party of China|Politburo Standing Committee]], was quoted in ''[[The Economist]]'' saying that the Confucius Institutes were \"an important part of China's overseas propaganda set-up\". The statement has been seized upon by critics as evidence of a politicized mission.<ref>[http://www.economist.com/node/14678507 A message from Confucius; New ways of projecting soft power], ''The Economist'', 22 October 2009.</ref> Many foreign scholars have characterized the CI program as an exercise in [[soft power]], expanding China's economic, cultural, and diplomatic reach through the promotion of Chinese language and culture,<ref>Peter Schmidt (2010b), [http://chronicle.texterity.com/chronicle/20101022a?pg=8#pg8 At U.S. Colleges, Chinese-Financed Centers Prompt Worries About Academic Freedom] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716214708/http://chronicle.texterity.com/chronicle/20101022a?pg=8#pg8 |date=16 July 2011 }}, The Chronicle of Higher Education, 17 September 2010.</ref><ref>Jae Park(2013),[https://dx.doi.org/10.1080/09620214.2013.770205/ Cultural artifact, ideology export or soft power? Confucius Institute in Peru], ''International Studies in Sociology of Education'', 23(1), 1\u201316.</ref> while others have suggested a possible role in intelligence collection.<ref name=\"Michel Juneau-Katsuya 2009. pp 160\">{{ill|Fabrice De Pierrebourg|fr}} and [[Michel Juneau-Katsuya]], ''Nest of Spies: The Startling Truth About Foreign Agents at Work Within Canada's Borders'', HarperCollins Canada, 2009. {{ISBN|1554684498}}. pp 160 \u2013 162</ref><ref name=\"canada.com\">Janet Steffenhagen, [http://www.canada.com/vancouversun/news/westcoastnews/story.html?id=179b4e77-f0cf-4608-a8b7-a9943116f489 'Has BCIT sold out to Chinese propaganda?'] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120822144124/http://www.canada.com/vancouversun/news/westcoastnews/story.html?id=179b4e77-f0cf-4608-a8b7-a9943116f489 |date=22 August 2012 }}, ''[[The Vancouver Sun]]'', 2 April 2008.</ref> The soft power goals also include assuaging concerns of a \"China threat\" in the context of the country's increasingly powerful economy and military.<ref>{{cite news|last=French|first=Howard W.|title=Another Chinese Export is All the Rage: China's Language|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/11/international/asia/11china.html?pagewanted=all|accessdate=3 July 2011|newspaper=The New York Times|date=11 January 2006}}</ref>\n\nRetired  British  diplomat  and  China  expert  Roger  Garside concludes  in  his  submission  to  the Conservative  Party  Human  Rights  Commission  that  \u201cacademic  freedom  is  inherently compromised  by  permitting  a  state  agency  controlled  by  the  Communist  Party  of  China  to establish  a  teaching  operation in  any school  or  university.\u201d<ref>[http://www.conservativehumanrights.com/news/2019/CPHRC_Confucius_Institutes_report_FEBRUARY_2019.pdf China's Confucius Institute: An Inquiry by the Conservative Party Human Rights Commission, February 2019]</ref>\n\nWhile Chinese authorities have been cautious not to have CIs act as direct promoters of the party's political viewpoints, a few suggest that the Confucius Institutes function in this way.{{whom|date=September 2019}} Officials say that one important goal of the Institutes is to influence other countries' view of China.<ref name=\"econ\">''[[The Economist]]'', [https://www.economist.com/blogs/asiaview/2011/01/china%E2%80%99s_confucius_institutes China\u2019s Confucius Institutes: Rectification of statues], \"Asia Banyan\", 20 January 2011.</ref> [[Peng Ming-min]], a [[Taiwan independence]] activist and politician, claims that colleges and universities where a Confucius Institute is established have to sign a contract in which they declare their support for Beijing's \"[[One China]]\" policy. As a result, both [[Taiwan]] and [[Tibet]] become taboo at the institutes.<ref>[[Peng Ming-min]] \u5f6d\u660e\u654f (2011), [http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/editorials/archives/2011/05/31/2003504575 China picks pockets of academics worldwide], ''[[Taipei Times]]'' Tue, 31 May 2011, p. 8.</ref> However, this claim is in dispute. Michael Nylan, professor of [[Chinese history]] at the [[University of California at Berkeley]], stated that CIs have become less heavy-handed in their demands, and have learnt from \"early missteps\", such as insisting that universities adopt a policy that Taiwan is part of China. Nylan's survey of faculty and administrators at fifteen universities with Confucius Institutes revealed two reports that institutes had exerted pressure to block guest speakers, but both events went ahead anyway.<ref>Golden (2011).</ref>\n\nThe CI's soft power goals are seen as an attempt by the PRC to modernize away from [[Propaganda in the Soviet Union|Soviet-influenced propaganda]] of the [[Propaganda in the People's Republic of China#Mao era|Maoist era]].<ref>{{Cite book|title = China's Thought Management|last = Brady|first = Anne-Marie|publisher = Routledge|year = 2011|isbn = 978-0415616737|location = London & New York|pages = 81}}</ref>{{whom|date=September 2019}} Other initiatives include [[Chinese contemporary art]] exhibitions, television programs, concerts by popular singers, translations of [[Chinese literature]], and the expansion of state-run news channels such as [[Xinhua News Agency]] and [[China Central Television]].<ref>James F. Paradise (2009), [http://wenku.baidu.com/view/3b7190f79e31433239689307.html China and International Harmony: The Role of Confucius Institutes in Bolstering Beijing's Soft Power], ''[[Asian Survey]]'' 49.4: 648\u2013649.</ref>\n\n==Organization==\n[[Hanban]] is a non-profit government organization,<ref>{{cite web|title=Hanban offers a wider choice|url=http://africa.chinadaily.com.cn/weekly/2013-09/13/content_16967993.htm|work=China Daily|author1=Sun Shangwu |author2=Zhao Huanxin |author3=Tang Yue |date=13 September 2013|quote=...Hanban, the nonprofit agency that administers Confucius Institutes worldwide.}}</ref> though it is connected with the Ministry of Education and has close ties to a number of senior [[Communist Party of China|Communist Party]] officials. The Confucius Institute headquarters in Beijing establishes the guidelines which the separate Confucius Institutes worldwide follows. The headquarters is governed by a council with fifteen members, ten of whom are directors of overseas institutes.<ref>{{cite web|title=Steven Knapp Named to Council of the Confucius Institute Headquarters|url=http://gwtoday.gwu.edu/steven-knapp-named-council-confucius-institute-headquarters|accessdate=21 April 2014|date=3 June 2013}}</ref> The Institutes themselves are individually managed under the leadership of their own board of directors, which should include members of the host institution.<ref>{{cite web|title=Constitution and By-Laws of the Confucius Institutes|url=http://english.hanban.org/node_7880.htm#no3|publisher=Hanban|accessdate=21 April 2014}}</ref> The current chair of the Confucius Institute Headquarters council is [[Liu Yandong]],<ref>{{cite web|title=VP calls for development of Confucius Institute|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2013-12/07/content_17159584.htm|agency=Xinhua News Agency|accessdate=21 April 2014|date=7 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.buffalo.edu/ubnow/campus.host.html/content/shared/university/news/ub-reporter-articles/stories/2016/12/confucius-institute-year.detail.html |title=UBCI named Confucius Institute of the Year |author=Bruce Acker |date=December 22, 2016 |accessdate=November 17, 2017}}</ref> a Chinese vice premier and member of the Chinese Communist Party Politburo who formerly headed the [[United Front Work Department]]. Other leaders of the council are similarly drawn from the Communist Party and central government agencies, such as the Ministry of Finance, Ministry of Education, and the State Council Information Office (also known as the Office of Overseas Propaganda).<ref name=ChinaU/><ref>{{cite web|title=COUNCIL MEMBERS OF THE CONFUCIUS INSTITUTE HEADQUARTERS IN 2011|url=http://www.chinese.cn/conference11/node_37099.htm#|accessdate=21 April 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150602083521/http://www.chinese.cn/conference11/node_37099.htm|archivedate=2 June 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The council sets the agenda for the Confucius Institutes and makes changes to the bylaws while other tasks and ongoing management of the Confucius Institute Headquarters are handled by the professional executive leadership headed by the director-general.<ref>{{cite web|title=About Us: Leadership|url=http://english.hanban.org/node_38839.htm|publisher=Hanban|accessdate=21 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Confucius Institute Headquarters|url=http://english.hanban.org/node_7716.htm|publisher=Hanban|accessdate=21 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe Chinese Government shares the burden of funding Confucius Institutes with host universities, and takes a hands-off approach to management.<ref name=\"The Economist(2009)\">{{cite news|title=A message from Confucius: New ways of projecting soft power|url=http://www.economist.com/node/14678507|accessdate=3 July 2011|newspaper=The Economist|date=22 October 2009}}</ref> The Institutes function independently within the guidelines established by Hanban and the Confucius Institute Headquarters. Each Institute is responsible for drawing up and managing their own budget, which is subject to approval by the headquarters. The Confucius Institute Headquarters provides various restrictions on how their funds may be used, including earmarking funds for specific purposes.<ref>{{cite web|title=Regulations for the Administration of Confucius Institute Headquarters Funds|url=http://english.hanban.org/article/2010-06/21/content_146458.htm|publisher=Hanban-News|accessdate=3 July 2011}}</ref> Institutes in the United States are generally provided with $100,000 annually from Hanban, with the local university required to match funding.<ref name=\"Schimdt 2010b\">Schimdt (2010b).</ref>\n\nIn addition to their local-partner university, Confucius Institutes operate in co-operation with a Chinese partner university.<ref>{{cite web|title=Confucius Institute at Tallinn University|url=http://www.tlu.ee/?LangID=2&CatID=5145|publisher=Tallinn University|accessdate=3 July 2011}}</ref> Many Institutes are governed by a board which is composed of several members from the Chinese partner school, with the remaining members affiliated with the local-partner university.<ref>{{cite web|title=Board of Directors|url=http://www.confuciusinstitute.buffalo.edu/people/board_of_directors/|publisher=University of Buffalo College of Arts and Sciences|accessdate=3 July 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120326130424/http://www.confuciusinstitute.buffalo.edu/people/board_of_directors/|archivedate=26 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}{{cite web|title=Governing and Advisory Boards|url=http://www.confucius.umn.edu/about/boards.html|publisher=Regents of the University of Minnesota|accessdate=3 July 2011}}{{cite web|title=Chinese language school in the world|url=https://www.cchatty.com/chineseschool/|publisher=Confucius Institute at the University of New South Wales|accessdate=3 July 2011}}</ref> At most Institutes, the director is appointed by the local partner university.<ref name=\"The Economist(2009)\" />\n\n==Hiring policy controversy==\nThe Hanban website stated that Chinese language instructors should be \"aged between 22 to 60, physical and mental healthy, no record of participation in [[Falun Gong]] and other illegal organizations, and no criminal record.\"<ref>Hanban, [http://www.chinese.cn/hanban_en/node_9806.htm \u2018Overseas Volunteer Chinese Teacher Program\u2019] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120122194907/http://www.chinese.cn/hanban_en/node_9806.htm |date=22 January 2012 }}. Retrieved 16 September 2011.</ref> In many universities, the employer is the Chinese government, not the university.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\nHuman rights lawyer Clive Ansley has argued that the part of the hiring policy that discriminates against Falun Gong believers is in contravention of anti-discrimination laws and human rights codes.<ref>Macleans, [http://oncampus.macleans.ca/education/2011/08/10/confucius-institutes-break-human-rights-rules/ Confucius Institutes break human rights rules:Profs working in Canada 'must have no record of Falun Gong'\"], 10 August 2011.</ref> Marci Hamilton, Paul R. Verkuil Chair in Public Law at [[Yeshiva University]], called this policy \"unethical and illegal in the free world.\"<ref name=Discrimination>Matthew Robertson, [http://www.theepochtimes.com/n2/united-states/at-us-universities-confucius-institutes-import-discrimination-60714.html\u201cAt US Universities, Confucius Institutes Import Discrimination\u201d], ''[[The Epoch Times]]'', 24 Aug 2011.{{unreliable source?|date=January 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, [[McMaster University]] in Canada closed its Confucius Institute due to hiring issues over Falun Gong.<ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/education/mcmaster-closing-confucius-institute-over-hiring-issues/article8372894/ McMaster closing Confucius Institute over hiring issues ], ''The Globe and Mail'', 7 February 2013.</ref>\n\n== Curriculum ==\nThe curriculum of Confucius Institutes is based on the institute's role as a language center.<ref name=\"econ\"/> Confucius Institutes teach [[simplified Chinese characters]], which are standard in Mainland China, rather than the [[traditional Chinese characters]] used in Taiwan and Hong Kong. Confucius Institutes provide a sanitized view of Chinese society which avoids contentious topics like [[human rights]] abuses and Tibet.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Power |first1=John |title=University of Queensland faces heat for naming Chinese diplomat Xu Jie as faculty member |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/asia/australasia/article/3019888/hong-kong-and-mainland-china-students-clash-rally-australian |website=www.scmp.com |publisher=South China Morning Post |accessdate=26 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Reception and controversies==\n{{Main|Criticism of Confucius Institutes}}\nIn the short time-frame of their rapid expansion, the Institutes have been the subject of much controversy. Criticisms of the Institutes have included administrative concerns about finance, academic viability, legal issues, and relations with the Chinese partner university, as well as broader concerns about improper influence over teaching and research, industrial and military espionage,<ref name=\"Michel Juneau-Katsuya 2009. pp 160\"/><ref name=\"canada.com\"/> surveillance of Chinese abroad, and undermining Taiwanese influence.<ref>Don Starr (2009), [http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1465-3435.2008.01371.x/full Chinese Language Education in Europe: the Confucius Institutes], ''European Journal of Education'' Volume 44, Issue 1, pages 78\u201379.</ref> There has also been organized opposition to the establishment of a Confucius Institute at [[University of Melbourne]],<ref>Geoff Maslen (2007), [http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=20071130094503100 Warning \u2013 be wary of Confucius institutes] University World News, 2 December 2007.</ref> [[University of Manitoba]],<ref>[http://oncampus.macleans.ca/education/2011/04/27/profs-worry-china-preparing-to-spy-on-students/ Profs worry China preparing to spy on students], ''Maclean's'', 27 April 2011.</ref> [[Stockholm University]],<ref>Starr (2009), p. 6.</ref><ref>\"i Kina \u00e4r tio miljoner barn utan en ordentlig skola\" [http://www.riksdagen.se/Webbnav/index.aspx?nid=101&bet=2007/08:46 Riksdagens snabbprotokoll 2007/08:46 (in Swedish)]</ref> [[University of Chicago]]<ref>Peter Schmidt (2010a), [http://chronicle.com/article/U-of-Chicagos-Plans-for-M/65737/ U. of Chicago's Plans for Milton Friedman Institute Stir Outrage on the Faculty], [[The Chronicle of Higher Education]], 1 June 2010.</ref> and many others. More significantly, some universities that hosted Confucius Institutes decided to terminate their contracts. These include Japan's [[Osaka Sangyo University]] in 2010;<ref>[http://english.peopledaily.com.cn/90001/90782/7023278.html Japanese university apologizes for calling Confucius Institute spy agency], ''People's Daily'', 12 June 2010.</ref> Canada's [[McMaster University]] and [[Universit\u00e9 de Sherbrooke]],<ref>James Bradshaw and Colin Freeze, [https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/education/mcmaster-closing-confucius-institute-over-hiring-issues/article8372894/ McMaster closing Confucius Institute over hiring issues], ''The Globe and Mail'', 7 February 2013.</ref><ref>Caroline Alphonso and Karen Howlett, [https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/toronto/toronto-school-board-seeks-end-to-china-deal/article19651681/ Toronto school board seeks end to China deal], ''The Globe and Mail'', 17 July 2014.</ref> and France's [[University of Lyon]] in 2013;<ref name=\"World should watch for Confucius\"/> the [[University of Chicago]], [[Pennsylvania State University]], and the [[Toronto District School Board]] in 2014,<ref name=\"insidehighered.com\">[https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2014/09/26/chicago-severs-ties-chinese-government-funded-confucius-institute Chicago to Close Confucius Institute], Inside Higher Ed, 26 September 2014</ref><ref>[http://www.la.psu.edu/news/confucius-institute-update Confucius Institute update], Penn State College of Liberal Arts, 1 October 2014.</ref><ref>[http://www.scmp.com/news/world/article/1628071/toronto-schools-reject-tie-chinas-confucius-institute Toronto schools reject tie-up with China\u2019s Confucius Institute], ''South China Morning Post'', 30 October 2014.</ref> the German [[Hochschule der Medien|Stuttgart Media University]] and [[University of Hohenheim]] in 2015,<ref>[https://www.insidehighered.com/quicktakes/2015/06/08/german-university-abandons-plans-confucius-institute German University Abandons Plans for Confucius Institute], ''Inside Higher Ed'', 8 June 2015.</ref><ref>[http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/13211073.Worldwide_campaign_launched_against_Confucius_Institutes/ Worldwide campaign launched against Confucius Institutes], ''The Sunday Herald'', 24 April 2015.</ref> and [[Vrije Universiteit Brussel]] in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tzu-ti |first1=Huang |title=Belgian university to shut down Confucius Institute |url=https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3835636 |website=www.taiwannews.com.tw |publisher=Taiwan News |accessdate=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Criticism of Confucius Institutes|Controversy regarding Confucius Institutes]]  in the US, Australian, and Canadian press includes criticism that unlike other governments' language and culture promotion organizations, the Confucius Institutes operate within established universities, colleges, and secondary schools around the world, providing funding, teachers and educational materials.<ref name=ChinaU>{{cite news|last=Sahlins|first=Marshall|title=China U.|url=http://www.thenation.com/article/176888/china-u#|accessdate=11 April 2014|newspaper=The Nation|date=29 October 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Michel Juneau-Katsuya 2009. pp 160\" /><ref name=\"abc.net.au\">{{cite news|last1=Cohen|first1=Hagar|title=Australian universities the latest battleground in Chinese soft power offensive|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-10-14/universities-latest-battleground-in-chinese-soft-power-offensive/7931958|accessdate=13 October 2016|agency=ABC Australia}}</ref> This has raised concerns over their influence on academic freedom, the possibility of [[industrial espionage]],<ref>[http://www.canada.com/vancouversun/news/westcoastnews/story.html?id=179b4e77-f0cf-4608-a8b7-a9943116f489 'Has BCIT sold out to Chinese propaganda?'] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120822144124/http://www.canada.com/vancouversun/news/westcoastnews/story.html?id=179b4e77-f0cf-4608-a8b7-a9943116f489 |date=22 August 2012 }}, The Vancouver Sun, 2 April 2008.</ref> and concerns that the institutes present a selective and politicized view of China as a means of advancing the country's [[soft power]] internationally.<ref name=ChinaU/><ref name=\"abc.net.au\"/><ref>[http://www.economist.com/node/17969895 China's Confucius Institutes: Rectification of Statues], ''The Economist'',  20 January 2011.</ref>\n\nUnderlying such opposition is concern by professors that a Confucius Institute would interfere with academic freedom and be able to pressure the university to censor speech on topics the [[Communist Party of China]] objects to.<ref>{{cite news|last=Guttenplan|first=D. D.|title=Critics Worry About Influence of Chinese Institutes on U.S. Campuses|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/05/us/critics-worry-about-influence-of-chinese-institutes-on-us-campuses.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=4 March 2012|authorlink=D. D. Guttenplan}}</ref> An article in [[The Chronicle of Higher Education]] asserts that there is little evidence of meddling from China, although the same article did go on to say the Institutes were \"distinct in the degree to which they were financed and managed by a foreign government.\"<ref name=\"Schimdt 2010b\" /> After interviewing China scholars, journalists and CI directors, a writer for ''[[The Diplomat]]'' also found little support for the concern that CIs would serve as propaganda vehicles, though some of her sources did note that they would face constraints in their curriculum on matters such as Tibet and human rights.<ref>Ulara Nakagawa. [http://the-diplomat.com/new-emissary/2011/03/07/confucius-controversy/ Confucius Controversy], ''[[The Diplomat]]''.</ref> An article in ''[[The New York Times]]'' quotes [[Arthur Waldron]], a professor of international relations at the [[University of Pennsylvania]], saying that the key issue is academic independence. \"Once you have a Confucius Institute on campus, you have a second source of opinions and authority that is ultimately answerable to the Chinese Communist Party and which is not subject to scholarly review.\"<ref>[[D. D. Guttenplan]] (2012), [https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/05/us/critics-worry-about-influence-of-chinese-institutes-on-us-campuses.html Critics Worry About Influence of Chinese Institutes on U.S. Campuses], ''The New York Times'', 4 March 2012.</ref>\n\nIn October 2013, University of Chicago professor Marshall Sahlins published an extensive investigative article criticizing the Confucius Institutes and the universities hosting them.<ref name=\"thenation.com\">\"[http://www.thenation.com/article/176888/china-u China U: Confucius Institutes censor political discussions and restrain the free exchange of ideas. Why, then, do American universities sponsor them?]\" By Marshall Sahlins. The Nation, 18 November 2013</ref> Later, more than 100 faculty members signed a protest against the Confucius Institute at the University of Chicago.<ref>''[http://www.insidehighered.com/news/2014/04/29/chicago-faculty-object-their-campuss-confucius-institute#sthash.DFh0XAAH.dpbs Rejecting Confucius Funding]'' Inside Higher Ed, 29 April 2014. By Elizabeth Redden</ref> In September 2014, the University of Chicago suspended its negotiation for renewal of the agreement with Hanban.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://news.uchicago.edu/article/2014/09/25/statement-confucius-institute-university-chicago|title = Statement on the Confucius Institute at the University of Chicago|date = 25 September 2014|accessdate = 25 September 2014|website = UChicago News|publisher = University of Chicago}}</ref> Two months later, the Canadian Association of University Teachers urged Canadian universities and colleges to end ties with the Confucius Institute.<ref>''[http://www.caut.ca/news/2013/12/17/universities-and-colleges-urged-to-end-ties-with-confucius-institutes Universities and colleges urged to end ties with Confucius Institutes] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140820210709/http://www.caut.ca/news/2013/12/17/universities-and-colleges-urged-to-end-ties-with-confucius-institutes |date=20 August 2014 }}\" Canadian Association of University Teachers, 17 December 2013</ref>\n\nIn June 2014, the American Association of University Professors issued a statement urging American universities to cease their collaboration with the Confucius Institute unless the universities can have unilateral control of the academia affairs, that the teachers in Confucius Institutes can have the same academic freedom enjoyed by other university faculty members, and that the agreements between universities and Confucius Institutes are available to the community.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://aaup.org/report/partnerships-foreign-governments-case-confucius-institutes|title = Our Partnerships with Foreign Governments: The Case of Confucius Institutes|date = June 2014|accessdate = 21 June 2014|website = American Association of University Professors}}</ref> The AAUP statement was widely noticed by US media and prompted extensive further debate in the US.<ref>''[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/china/10907971/US-professors-urge-Western-universities-to-end-ties-to-Chinas-Confucius-Institutes.html US professors urge Western universities to end ties to China's Confucius Institutes]'' By Peter Foster, Washington. The Telegraph (London), 18 June 2014.</ref><ref>''[http://chronicle.com/article/AAUP-Rebukes-Colleges-for/147153/ AAUP Rebukes Colleges for Chinese Institutes, and Censures Northeastern Ill]'' Peter Schmidt, The Chronicle of Higher Education, 15 June 2014</ref><ref>''[https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/higher-education/us-professors-troubled-by-confucius-institutes/2014/06/23/d178eeba-fae5-11e3-9f27-09f20b8bfd1a_story.html US Professors Troubled by Confucius Institutes]'' Carolyn Thompson. 24 June 2014.</ref><ref>''[https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/the-price-of-confucius-institutes/2014/06/21/4d7598f2-f7b6-11e3-a3a5-42be35962a52_story.html The price of Confucius Institutes]'' Washington Post, Editorial Board 21 June 2014</ref>\n\nTwo months later, in August 2014, Xu Lin, Director-General of the Hanban and Chief Executive of the CIs worldwide, became embroiled in an [[Braga Incident|incident in Braga, Portugal]], when Xu ordered her staff to rip pages referring to Taiwanese academic institutions from the published program for the [[European Association for Chinese Studies]] conference in [[Braga]], claiming the materials were \"contrary to Chinese regulations\".<ref name=\"China's Soft-Power Fail\">[http://www.bloombergview.com/articles/2014-10-07/china-s-soft-power-fail China's Soft-Power Fail], Bloomberg View, 7 October 2014.</ref> ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' described Xu's attempted censorship as the \"bullying approach to academic freedom\".<ref name=\"online.wsj.com\">[https://www.wsj.com/articles/beijings-propaganda-lessons-1407430440 Beijing's Propaganda Lessons: Confucius Institute officials are agents of Chinese censorship], The Wall Street Journal, 7 August 2014.</ref>\n\nIn September 2014, the [[University of Chicago]] closed their CI after pressure from faculty members, blaming Xu's comments that her threatening letter and phone call forced the university to continue hosting the institute.<ref name=\"insidehighered.com\"/><ref name=Redden>{{cite web|last1=Redden|first1=Elizabeth|title=Chicago to Close Confucius Institute|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2014/09/26/chicago-severs-ties-chinese-government-funded-confucius-institute|publisher=[[Inside Higher Ed]]|accessdate=28 September 2014}}</ref> The ''[[Business Spectator]]'' concludes that the Xu Lin's hardline behavior highlights one of the biggest problems for Beijing's charm offensive. \"It still relies on officials like Xu, who still think and act like party ideologues who like to assert their authority and bully people into submission.\"<ref>[http://www.businessspectator.com.au/article/2014/9/29/china/hard-times-chinas-soft-power Hard times for China's soft power], Business Spectator, 29 September 2014.</ref> Less than a week later, [[Pennsylvania State University]] also cut ties with the Confucius Institute after coming to the conclusion that \"its objectives were not in line with the Institute's\".<ref name=\"Belkin, Douglas\">{{cite news |url = https://www.wsj.com/articles/penn-state-latest-school-to-drop-chinas-confucius-institute-1412196655|title = Penn State Latest School to Drop China's Confucius Institute|work = The Wall Street Journal|date = 1 October 2014|accessdate = 3 October 2014|author = Belkin, Douglas}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2014, [[Stockholm University]], the first university in Europe to host a Confucius Institute, announced it was terminating the program. Press coverage of the [[Braga incident]] in the Swedish press was said to have influenced the decision. \"Generally it is questionable to have, within the framework of the university, institutes that are financed by another country,\" said the university's chancellor.<ref>[https://networks.h-net.org/node/22055/discussions/56521/stockholm-university-terminating-its-confucius-institute Stockholm University terminating its Confucius Institute]</ref>\n\nIn the same month, the [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on Africa, Global Health, Global Human Rights and International Organizations]] held a hearing entitled \"Is Academic Freedom Threatened by China's Influence on U.S. Universities?\".<ref>[http://foreignaffairs.house.gov/hearing/subcommittee-hearing-academic-freedom-threatened-chinas-influence-us-universities Subcommittee Hearing: Is Academic Freedom Threatened by China's Influence on U.S. Universities?], House Committee on Foreign Affairs, 4 December 2014.</ref> Chairman [[Chris Smith (New Jersey politician)|Chris Smith]] said, \"U.S. colleges and universities should not be outsourcing academic control, faculty and student oversight or curriculum to a foreign government\", and called for a [[Government Accountability Office|GAO]] study into agreements between American universities and China.<ref>[http://www.latimes.com/nation/la-na-chinese-influence-20141205-story.html China's influence threatens American universities, experts say], ''Los Angeles Times'', 4 December 2014.</ref> On 5 December 2014, PRC [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the People's Republic of China|Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] spokeswoman [[Hua Chunying]] denied the House testimony and said \"We have assisted with supplying teachers and textbooks at the request of the U.S. side but have never interfered with academic freedom.\"<ref>[https://blogs.wsj.com/chinarealtime/2014/12/05/china-says-its-never-interfered-with-u-s-academic-freedom/ China Says It\u2019s 'Never Interfered With U.S. Academic Freedom'], Chinarealtime, ''The Wall Street Journal'', 5 December 2014.</ref>\n\nControversy continued in 2018 as U.S. Congress members from [[Texas]] wrote a letter to four universities in that state urging them to close their Confucius Institutes.  [[Texas A&M]] did so shortly after receiving the letter.<ref name=2018_Texas_AM_closure>{{Cite web |url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2018/04/09/texas-am-cuts-ties-confucius-institutes-response-congressmens-concerns |title=Closing a Confucius Institute, at Congressmen's Request |author=Elizabeth Redden |date=April 9, 2018 |accessdate=April 9, 2018}}</ref> Throughout 2018 and 2019, all of the institutes in TFlorida were closed: the [[University of West Florida]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/quicktakes/2018/02/06/more-scrutiny-confucius-institutes-one-close|title=More Scrutiny for Confucius Institutes; One to Close {{!}} Inside Higher Ed|website=www.insidehighered.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> the [[University of North Florida]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/quicktakes/2018/08/16/north-florida-will-close-confucius-institute|title=North Florida Will Close Confucius Institute|last=Redden|first=Elizabeth|date=Aug 16, 2018|work=Inside Higher Ed|access-date=Jan 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>, the [[University of South Florida]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2019/01/09/colleges-move-close-chinese-government-funded-confucius-institutes-amid-increasing|title=Colleges move to close Chinese government-funded Confucius Institutes amid increasing scrutiny|website=www.insidehighered.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> and [[Miami Dade College]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://politi.co/2zUofIt|title=Miami Dade College is shutting down its Confucius Institute|last=Andrew Atterbury|website=Politico PRO|language=en|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref>\n\nA U.S. law passed in 2019 that prohibits universities hosting Confucius Institutes from receiving funding for Chinese language studies from the Department of Defense led to more closures of Confucius Institutes. Unable to obtained a waiver from the Department of Defense, [[Indiana University]], the [[University of Minnesota]], the [[University of Rhode Island]], [[San Francisco State University]], the [[University of Oregon]], [[Western Kentucky University]], [[Arizona State University]], the [[University of Hawaii at Manoa]], and [[San Diego State University]] closed their the programs in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/quicktakes/2019/05/01/3-more-universities-close-confucius-institutes|title=3 More Universities Close Confucius Institutes {{!}} Inside Higher Ed|website=www.insidehighered.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.chronicle.com/article/Another-Confucius-Institute/247025|title=Another Confucius Institute Closes|last=Fischer|first=Karin|date=2019-08-28|work=The Chronicle of Higher Education|access-date=2020-01-20|language=en-US|issn=0009-5982}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2019/07/29/hawaii-news/university-of-hawaiis-confucius-institute-closes-as-fbi-raises-alarm/|title=University of Hawaii's Confucius Institute closes as FBI raises alarm|last=wcole@staradvertiser.com|first=By William Cole|last2=July 29|first2=2019|date=2019-07-29|website=Honolulu Star-Advertiser|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/asian-america/u-s-colleges-face-tough-choice-take-money-china-lose-n1055871|title=U.S. colleges face tough choice: Take money from China and lose federal funding|website=NBC News|language=en|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> In 2020, the [[University of Maryland]] also announced the closure of its Confucius Institute, the oldest one in the U.S..<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wamu.org/story/20/01/17/following-federal-pressure-umd-will-close-a-program-that-had-chinese-government-support/|title=Following Federal Pressure, UMD Will Close A Program That Had Chinese Government Support|website=WAMU|language=en|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> \n\nOn 19 February 2019, [[Leiden University]] in The Netherlands promised to end its agreement with Confucius Institute in August 2019. <ref name=\"2019_Leiden\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.universiteitleiden.nl/en/news/2019/02/confusius-instituut-en|title=Leiden University to end agreement with Confucius Institute |date=February 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Chinese Bridge]]\n*[[Istituto Italiano di Cultura]]\n*[[Dante Alighieri Society]]\n*[[Goethe-Institut]]\n*[[Instituto Cam\u00f5es]]\n*[[Instituto Cervantes]]\n*[[Institut Fran\u00e7ais]]\n*China's \"[[Propaganda in the People's Republic of China#Soft power initiative|soft power initiative]]\"\n*[[Propaganda in the People's Republic of China]]\n*[[Panda diplomacy]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite journal |last1=Biswas |first1=Asit K. |last2=Hartley |first2=Kris |title=China\u2019s soft power struggles. |journal=Asia and the Pacific Policy Society |date=2017 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Asit_Biswas/publication/320961581_China's_soft_power_struggles/links/5a04b49c0f7e9bc4078ecc5e/Chinas-soft-power-struggles.pdf |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Callahan |first1=William A. |title=Identity and security in China: the negative soft power of the China dream |journal=Politics |date=2015 |volume=35 |issue=3-4 |pages=216-229 |url=http://eprints.lse.ac.uk/64455/1/__lse.ac.uk_storage_LIBRARY_Secondary_libfile_shared_repository_Content_Callahan,%20W_Identity%20and%20security_Callahan_Identity%20and%20security_2015.pdf |accessdate=18 April 2020 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Hubbert |first1=Jennifer. |title=China in the World: An Anthropology of Confucius Institutes, Soft Power, and Globalization |date=2019 |publisher=University of Hawai\u2018i Press |pages=viii + 234 |url=https://www.h-net.org/reviews/showpdf.php?id=54259 |accessdate=18 April 2020 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Lahtinen |first1=Anja |title=China's soft power: Challenges of Confucianism and Confucius Institutes |journal=Journal of Comparative Asian Development |date=2015 |volume=14 |issue=2 |pages=200-226 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Anja_Lahtinen/publication/282204244_China%27s_Soft_Power_Challenges_of_Confucianism_and_Confucius_Institutes/links/5addd5e90f7e9b285941aa66/Chinas-Soft-Power-Challenges-of-Confucianism-and-Confucius-Institutes.pdf |accessdate=18 April 2020 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Peterson |first1=Rachelle |title=Outsourced to China: Confucius Institutes and Soft Power in American Higher Education. A Report by the National Association of Scholars |date=2017 |publisher=National Association of Scholars |url=https://files.eric.ed.gov/fulltext/ED580866.pdf |accessdate=18 April 2020 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Procopio |first1=Maddalena |title=The effectiveness of Confucius Institutes as a tool of China\u2019s soft power in South Africa |journal=African East-Asian Affairs |date=2015 |issue=1-2 |url=http://aeaa.journals.ac.za/pub/article/download/155/111 |accessdate=18 April 2020 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Tella |first1=Oluwaseun |title=Wielding soft power in strategic regions: an analysis of China\u2019s power of attraction in Africa and the Middle East |journal=Africa Review |date=2 July 2016 |volume=8 |issue=2 |pages=133-144 |doi=10.1080/09744053.2016.1186868 |url=https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/09744053.2016.1186868 |accessdate=18 April 2020 |ref=harv |issn=0974-4053}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Zhou |first1=Ying |last2=Luk |first2=Sabrina |title=Establishing Confucius Institutes: a tool for promoting China\u2019s soft power? |journal=Journal of Contemporary China |date=2016 |volume=25 |issue=100 |pages=628-642 |ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Confucius Institute}}\n{{Library resources box}}\n*[http://www.chinesecio.com/ Confucius Institute Online] {{in lang|zh}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20061209220936/http://english.hanban.edu.cn/ China National Office for Teaching Chinese as a Foreign Language] {{in lang|zh}}\n*[http://confuciusinstitute.unl.edu/institutes.shtml List of Confucius Institutes around the world]\n* Pella, John & Erik Ringmar, \"[http://www.irhistory.info/index.php/confucius-and-the-jesuits Kongzi and his institutes],\" ''History of International Relations Open Textbook Project,'' Cambridge: Open Book, forthcoming.\n*[https://www.youtube.com/user/pricklyparadigmtv Sahlins on Confucius Institutes], four-part lecture by [[Marshall Sahlins]], PricklyParadigmTV, YouTube.\n*[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-30567743 Confucius institute: The hard side of China's soft power], Xu Lin interview, BBC News, 21 December 2014.\n\n{{International cultural promotion organizations}}\n\n[[Category:Chinese-language education]]\n[[Category:Confucius]]\n[[Category:Confucius Institute| ]]\n[[Category:Cultural promotion organizations]]\n[[Category:Foreign relations of China]]\n[[Category:Language advocacy organizations]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 2004]]\n[[Category:Sinology]]\n[[Category:2004 establishments in China]]\n[[Category:Organizations associated with the Communist Party of China]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Chinese government education, propaganda, and advocacy program promoting Mandarin Chinese and Chinese culture with a global focus}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| name = Confucius Institute\n| logo =  Confucious Institute logo.svg\n| logo_size = 150px\n| type = Cultural promotion organization\n| founded_date = {{start date and age|2004}}\n| location = 129 Deshengmen Outer Street, [[Xicheng District]], [[Beijing]]\n| key_people =\n| area_served = Worldwide\n| focus = [[Chinese culture]], [[Chinese language]]\n| method = Education and Advocacy\n| revenue =\n| endowment =\n| num_volunteers =\n| num_employees =\n| num_members =\n| owner = [[Ministry of Education of the People's Republic of China]]\n| Non-profit_slogan =\n| homepage = {{url|http://www.hanban.org/}}\n| dissolved =\n| footnotes =\n}}\n{{Chinese|s=\u5b54\u5b50\u5b66\u9662|t=\u5b54\u5b50\u5b78\u9662|p=K\u01d2ngz\u01d0 Xu\u00e9yu\u00e0n}}\n\n[[File:ICB-facade.JPG|thumb|Confucius Institute of [[Brittany (administrative region)|Brittany]] in [[Rennes]], France]]\n[[File:SenecaConfuciusInstitute2.jpg|thumb|A Confucius Institute at [[Seneca College]] in [[Toronto]], [[Canada]]]]\n\n'''Confucius Institute''' ({{zh|s = {{linktext|\u5b54\u5b50\u5b66\u9662}}|p = K\u01d2ngz\u01d0 Xu\u00e9yu\u00e0n}}) is a  public [[education]]al organization under the [[Ministry of Education of the People's Republic of China]],<ref name=ChinaU/> whose stated aim is to promote Chinese language and [[Culture of China|culture]], support local [[TCFL|Chinese teaching]] internationally, and facilitate cultural exchanges.<ref>{{cite news|last=Penn|first=Brierley|title=China Business:A broader education|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/china-business-2013/news/article.cfm?c_id=1503331&objectid=11238085|work=The New Zealand Herald|accessdate=21 April 2014|date=2014-04-15}}</ref><ref name=mattis>{{cite web|last=Mattis|first=Peter|title=Reexamining the Confucian Institutes|url=http://thediplomat.com/2012/08/reexamining-the-confucian-institutes/|work=The Diplomat|accessdate=21 April 2014|date=2 August 2012}}</ref> The organization has been criticized due to concerns of rising Chinese influences in the countries in which it operates.<ref>[http://www.economist.com/node/14678507 A message from Confucius; New ways of projecting soft power], ''The Economist'', 22 October 2009.</ref>\n\nThe Confucius Institute program began in 2004 and is overseen by [[Hanban]] (officially the Office of Chinese Language Council International). The institutes operate in co-operation with local affiliate colleges and universities around the world, and financing is shared between Hanban and the host institutions. The related Confucius Classroom program partners with local secondary schools or school districts to provide teachers and instructional materials.<ref>{{cite web|title=Introduction to the Confucius Institutes|url=http://college.chinese.cn/en/article/2009-08/29/content_22308.htm|accessdate=2 July 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707081524/http://college.chinese.cn/en/article/2009-08/29/content_22308.htm|archivedate=7 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author1=Jianguo Chen |author2=Chuang Wang |author3=Jinfa Cai |title=Teaching and learning Chinese: issues and perspectives|year=2010|publisher=IAP|pages=xix|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pGURhDOkdxEC&pg=PR19|isbn=9781617350641 }}</ref>\n\nChina has compared Confucius Institutes to language and culture promotion organizations such as Portugal's [[Instituto Cam\u00f5es]], Britain's [[British Council]], France's [[Alliance Fran\u00e7aise]], Italy's [[Societ\u00e0 Dante Alighieri]], Spain's [[Instituto Cervantes]] and Germany's [[Goethe-Institut]]\u2014several of them named for an iconic cultural figure identified with that country, as Confucius is identified with China.<ref name=20110220smh>Justin Norrie (2011), [http://www.smh.com.au/national/education/confucius-says-schools-in-but-dont-mention-democracy-20110219-1b09x.html Confucius says school's in, but don't mention democracy], ''The Sydney Morning Herald'', 20 February 2011.</ref> However, unlike these organizations, many Confucius Institutes operate directly on university campuses, thus giving rise to unique concerns related to academic freedom and political influence.<ref name=ChinaU/>\n\n==History==\nThe first Confucius Institute (CI) opened on 21 November 2004 in [[Seoul]], South Korea, after establishing a pilot institute in [[Tashkent]], Uzbekistan in June 2004. The CI in South Korea is no longer active. The second Confucius Institute was opened on the campus of the [[University of Maryland, College Park]], also in November 2004.<ref>[http://globalmaryland.umd.edu/offices/confucius-institute-maryland/frequently-asked-questions FAQ: When was CIM established?]</ref> Hundreds more have opened since in dozens of countries around the world, with the highest concentration of Institutes in the United States, Japan, and South Korea.<ref>{{cite book|last=Simon|first=Tay|title=Asia Alone: The Dangerous Post-Crisis Divide from America|year=2010|publisher=John Wiley and Sons|pages=42|url=https://books.google.com/?id=H-O-wYKRyGcC&pg=PA42#v=onepage&f=false|isbn=9780470826201}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2007, the first research-based Confucius Institute opened in [[Waseda University]] in Japan. In partnership with [[Peking University]], the program promotes research activities of graduate students studying Chinese.<ref>{{cite web|title=Signing of Waseda University Confucius Institute Agreement Established as the first Research Confucius Institute in collaboration with Peking University|url=http://www.waseda.jp/eng/news07/070412e.html|publisher=Waseda University|accessdate=11 July 2011}}</ref> \n\nAs of 2019, there are 530 Confucius Institutes in dozens of countries on six continents.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://english.hanban.org/node_10971.htm|title=HanBan-Confucius Institute/ClassRoom-About\u00a0Confucius Institute/ClassRoom|website=english.hanban.org|access-date=2019-10-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Confucius Institutes Worldwide|url=http://www.confucius.ucla.edu/about-us/confucius-institutes-worldwide|publisher=UCLA Confucious Institute|accessdate=11 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://confuciusinstitute.unl.edu/institutes.shtml | title=Confucius Institutes Around the Globe &#124; Confucius Institute &#124; Nebraska}}</ref> The Ministry of Education estimates that 100 million people overseas may be learning Chinese by 2010 and the program is expanding rapidly in order to keep up.<ref>[http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2007-12/06/content_7212089.htm China to host second Confucius Institute Conference], Xinhua, 6 December 2007.</ref> \n\nHanban aims to establish 1,000 Confucius Institutes by 2020.<ref>[http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2006-10/02/content_5521722.htm Confucius Institute: promoting language, culture and friendliness] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021071750/http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2006-10/02/content_5521722.htm |date=21 October 2012 }}, Xinhua, 2 October 2006.</ref>\n\n==Name==\nThe Confucius Institute is named after the noted Chinese philosopher [[Confucius]] (551\u2013479 BC). Throughout the 20th century, [[Communist Party of China]] (CPC) leaders criticized and denounced Confucius as the personification of China's \"feudal\" traditions, with [[Chen Duxiu#Anti-Confucianism|anti-Confucianism]] ranging from the 1912 [[New Culture Movement]] to the 1973 [[Criticize Lin, Criticize Confucius]] campaign during the [[Cultural Revolution]].<ref>Starr (2009), p. 68.</ref> However, in recent decades, interest in pre-modern Chinese culture has grown in the country, and Confucius in particular has seen a resurgence in popularity.<ref>{{cite news|last=Melvin|first=Sheila|title=Yu Dan and China's Return to Confucius|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/08/29/arts/29iht-melvin.1.7298367.html|accessdate=2 July 2011|newspaper=The New York Times|date=29 August 2007}}</ref> Outside of China, Confucius is a generally recognizable symbol of [[Chinese culture]], removed from the negative associations of other prominent Chinese figures such as chairman [[Mao Zedong]].<ref>{{cite news|title=China's Confucius Institutes Rectification of statues|url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/asiaview/2011/01/china\u2019s_confucius_institutes?page=1|accessdate=2 July 2011|newspaper=The Economist|date=20 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n\"Confucius Institute\" is a trademarked [[brand|brand name]], which according to a spokesman for the organisation, \"Those who enjoy more brand names will enjoy higher popularity, reputation, more social influence, and will therefore be able to generate more support from local communities.\"<ref>Starr (2009), p. 69.</ref> A 2011 crackdown protected \"Confucius Institute\" from [[Trademark#Registration|preregistration]] infringement in Costa Rica.<ref>Zhou Wenting, [http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/cndy/2011-07/29/content_13006180.htm Trademark infringement continues despite crackdown], ''China Daily'' 29 July 2011.</ref>\n\nA ''[[The China Post|China Post]]'' article reported in 2014 that \"Certainly, China would have made little headway if it had named these Mao Institutes, or even Deng Xiaoping Institutes. But by borrowing the name Confucius, it created a brand that was instantly recognized as a symbol of Chinese culture, radically different from the image of the Communist Party.\"<ref name=\"World should watch for Confucius\">[http://www.chinapost.com.tw/commentary/the-china-post/frank-ching/2014/10/01/418395/World-should.htm World should watch for Confucius], ''China Post'', 1 October 2014</ref>\n\nKerry Brown, Professor of Chinese Politics at the [[University of Sydney]], notes the irony that the CPC now lionizing Confucius had vilified him just four decades previously for his association with patriarchal, hierarchical, and conservative values.<ref>Kerry Brown, [http://www.scmp.com/comment/insight-opinion/article/1523308/case-eliminating-confucius-chinas-confucius-institutes The case for eliminating Confucius from China's Confucius Institutes], South China Morning Post, 2 June 2014.</ref>\n\n==Purpose==\n[[File:Signing ceremony (6943869420).jpg|thumb|262x262px|[[United Kingdom|British]] [[Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs|Foreign Secretary]] [[William Hague]] and Li Changchun at a signing ceremony in [[London]], 17 April 2012, for the agreement between Confucius Institute of China and [[Bangor University]] on the establishment of Confucius Institute at Bangor University, [[United Kingdom]]. The agreement was signed by John Hughes, [[Vice-Chancellor]] of Bangor University, and Xu Lin, Director of the Confucius Institute.]]\nConfucius Institutes (CIs) promote and teach Chinese culture and language around the world. CIs develop Chinese language courses, train teachers, hold the [[Hanyu Shuiping Kaoshi|HSK]] Examination (Chinese proficiency test), host cultural and artistic presentations, and provide information about contemporary China.<ref>{{cite web|title=About Us|url=http://about.chinese.cn/en/node_4221.htm|publisher=Confucius Institute|accessdate=3 July 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110811021842/http://about.chinese.cn/en/node_4221.htm|archivedate=11 August 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The director of the CI program, [[Xu Lin (Hanban)|Xu Lin]], stated that CIs were started to cater to the sudden uptick in interest of the Chinese language around the world. They also provide Chinese language teaching staff from Mainland China. As of 2011, there were 200 such teachers working in the United States.<ref>{{cite book|title=Teaching and Learning Chinese in Global Contexts|year=2011|publisher=Continuum International Publishing Group|url=https://books.google.com/?id=4q53niG5MLIC&pg=PA2#v=onepage&f=false|author1=Linda Tsung |author2=Ken Cruickshank |page=151|isbn=9781441100399}}</ref>\n\n==Political goals==\nThe Confucius Institute also has non-academic goals. [[Li Changchun]], the 5th-highest-ranking member of the [[Politburo Standing Committee of the Communist Party of China|Politburo Standing Committee]], was quoted in ''[[The Economist]]'' saying that the Confucius Institutes were \"an important part of China's overseas propaganda set-up\". The statement has been seized upon by critics as evidence of a politicized mission.<ref>[http://www.economist.com/node/14678507 A message from Confucius; New ways of projecting soft power], ''The Economist'', 22 October 2009.</ref> Many foreign scholars have characterized the CI program as an exercise in [[soft power]], expanding China's economic, cultural, and diplomatic reach through the promotion of Chinese language and culture,<ref>Peter Schmidt (2010b), [http://chronicle.texterity.com/chronicle/20101022a?pg=8#pg8 At U.S. Colleges, Chinese-Financed Centers Prompt Worries About Academic Freedom] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716214708/http://chronicle.texterity.com/chronicle/20101022a?pg=8#pg8 |date=16 July 2011 }}, The Chronicle of Higher Education, 17 September 2010.</ref><ref>Jae Park(2013),[https://dx.doi.org/10.1080/09620214.2013.770205/ Cultural artifact, ideology export or soft power? Confucius Institute in Peru], ''International Studies in Sociology of Education'', 23(1), 1\u201316.</ref> while others have suggested a possible role in intelligence collection.<ref name=\"Michel Juneau-Katsuya 2009. pp 160\">{{ill|Fabrice De Pierrebourg|fr}} and [[Michel Juneau-Katsuya]], ''Nest of Spies: The Startling Truth About Foreign Agents at Work Within Canada's Borders'', HarperCollins Canada, 2009. {{ISBN|1554684498}}. pp 160 \u2013 162</ref><ref name=\"canada.com\">Janet Steffenhagen, [http://www.canada.com/vancouversun/news/westcoastnews/story.html?id=179b4e77-f0cf-4608-a8b7-a9943116f489 'Has BCIT sold out to Chinese propaganda?'] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120822144124/http://www.canada.com/vancouversun/news/westcoastnews/story.html?id=179b4e77-f0cf-4608-a8b7-a9943116f489 |date=22 August 2012 }}, ''[[The Vancouver Sun]]'', 2 April 2008.</ref> The soft power goals also include assuaging concerns of a \"China threat\" in the context of the country's increasingly powerful economy and military.<ref>{{cite news|last=French|first=Howard W.|title=Another Chinese Export is All the Rage: China's Language|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/11/international/asia/11china.html?pagewanted=all|accessdate=3 July 2011|newspaper=The New York Times|date=11 January 2006}}</ref>\n\nRetired  British  diplomat  and  China  expert  Roger  Garside concludes  in  his  submission  to  the Conservative  Party  Human  Rights  Commission  that  \u201cacademic  freedom  is  inherently compromised  by  permitting  a  state  agency  controlled  by  the  Communist  Party  of  China  to establish  a  teaching  operation in  any school  or  university.\u201d<ref>[http://www.conservativehumanrights.com/news/2019/CPHRC_Confucius_Institutes_report_FEBRUARY_2019.pdf China's Confucius Institute: An Inquiry by the Conservative Party Human Rights Commission, February 2019]</ref>\n\nWhile Chinese authorities have been cautious not to have CIs act as direct promoters of the party's political viewpoints, a few suggest that the Confucius Institutes function in this way.{{whom|date=September 2019}} Officials say that one important goal of the Institutes is to influence other countries' view of China.<ref name=\"econ\">''[[The Economist]]'', [https://www.economist.com/blogs/asiaview/2011/01/china%E2%80%99s_confucius_institutes China\u2019s Confucius Institutes: Rectification of statues], \"Asia Banyan\", 20 January 2011.</ref> [[Peng Ming-min]], a [[Taiwan independence]] activist and politician, claims that colleges and universities where a Confucius Institute is established have to sign a contract in which they declare their support for Beijing's \"[[One China]]\" policy. As a result, both [[Taiwan]] and [[Tibet]] become taboo at the institutes.<ref>[[Peng Ming-min]] \u5f6d\u660e\u654f (2011), [http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/editorials/archives/2011/05/31/2003504575 China picks pockets of academics worldwide], ''[[Taipei Times]]'' Tue, 31 May 2011, p. 8.</ref> However, this claim is in dispute. Michael Nylan, professor of [[Chinese history]] at the [[University of California at Berkeley]], stated that CIs have become less heavy-handed in their demands, and have learnt from \"early missteps\", such as insisting that universities adopt a policy that Taiwan is part of China. Nylan's survey of faculty and administrators at fifteen universities with Confucius Institutes revealed two reports that institutes had exerted pressure to block guest speakers, but both events went ahead anyway.<ref>Golden (2011).</ref>\n\nThe CI's soft power goals are seen as an attempt by the PRC to modernize away from [[Propaganda in the Soviet Union|Soviet-influenced propaganda]] of the [[Propaganda in the People's Republic of China#Mao era|Maoist era]].<ref>{{Cite book|title = China's Thought Management|last = Brady|first = Anne-Marie|publisher = Routledge|year = 2011|isbn = 978-0415616737|location = London & New York|pages = 81}}</ref>{{whom|date=September 2019}} Other initiatives include [[Chinese contemporary art]] exhibitions, television programs, concerts by popular singers, translations of [[Chinese literature]], and the expansion of state-run news channels such as [[Xinhua News Agency]] and [[China Central Television]].<ref>James F. Paradise (2009), [http://wenku.baidu.com/view/3b7190f79e31433239689307.html China and International Harmony: The Role of Confucius Institutes in Bolstering Beijing's Soft Power], ''[[Asian Survey]]'' 49.4: 648\u2013649.</ref>\n\n==Organization==\n[[Hanban]] is a non-profit government organization,<ref>{{cite web|title=Hanban offers a wider choice|url=http://africa.chinadaily.com.cn/weekly/2013-09/13/content_16967993.htm|work=China Daily|author1=Sun Shangwu |author2=Zhao Huanxin |author3=Tang Yue |date=13 September 2013|quote=...Hanban, the nonprofit agency that administers Confucius Institutes worldwide.}}</ref> though it is connected with the Ministry of Education and has close ties to a number of senior [[Communist Party of China|Communist Party]] officials. The Confucius Institute headquarters in Beijing establishes the guidelines which the separate Confucius Institutes worldwide follows. The headquarters is governed by a council with fifteen members, ten of whom are directors of overseas institutes.<ref>{{cite web|title=Steven Knapp Named to Council of the Confucius Institute Headquarters|url=http://gwtoday.gwu.edu/steven-knapp-named-council-confucius-institute-headquarters|accessdate=21 April 2014|date=3 June 2013}}</ref> The Institutes themselves are individually managed under the leadership of their own board of directors, which should include members of the host institution.<ref>{{cite web|title=Constitution and By-Laws of the Confucius Institutes|url=http://english.hanban.org/node_7880.htm#no3|publisher=Hanban|accessdate=21 April 2014}}</ref> The current chair of the Confucius Institute Headquarters council is [[Liu Yandong]],<ref>{{cite web|title=VP calls for development of Confucius Institute|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2013-12/07/content_17159584.htm|agency=Xinhua News Agency|accessdate=21 April 2014|date=7 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.buffalo.edu/ubnow/campus.host.html/content/shared/university/news/ub-reporter-articles/stories/2016/12/confucius-institute-year.detail.html |title=UBCI named Confucius Institute of the Year |author=Bruce Acker |date=December 22, 2016 |accessdate=November 17, 2017}}</ref> a Chinese vice premier and member of the Chinese Communist Party Politburo who formerly headed the [[United Front Work Department]]. Other leaders of the council are similarly drawn from the Communist Party and central government agencies, such as the Ministry of Finance, Ministry of Education, and the State Council Information Office (also known as the Office of Overseas Propaganda).<ref name=ChinaU/><ref>{{cite web|title=COUNCIL MEMBERS OF THE CONFUCIUS INSTITUTE HEADQUARTERS IN 2011|url=http://www.chinese.cn/conference11/node_37099.htm#|accessdate=21 April 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150602083521/http://www.chinese.cn/conference11/node_37099.htm|archivedate=2 June 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The council sets the agenda for the Confucius Institutes and makes changes to the bylaws while other tasks and ongoing management of the Confucius Institute Headquarters are handled by the professional executive leadership headed by the director-general.<ref>{{cite web|title=About Us: Leadership|url=http://english.hanban.org/node_38839.htm|publisher=Hanban|accessdate=21 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Confucius Institute Headquarters|url=http://english.hanban.org/node_7716.htm|publisher=Hanban|accessdate=21 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe Chinese Government shares the burden of funding Confucius Institutes with host universities, and takes a hands-off approach to management.<ref name=\"The Economist(2009)\">{{cite news|title=A message from Confucius: New ways of projecting soft power|url=http://www.economist.com/node/14678507|accessdate=3 July 2011|newspaper=The Economist|date=22 October 2009}}</ref> The Institutes function independently within the guidelines established by Hanban and the Confucius Institute Headquarters. Each Institute is responsible for drawing up and managing their own budget, which is subject to approval by the headquarters. The Confucius Institute Headquarters provides various restrictions on how their funds may be used, including earmarking funds for specific purposes.<ref>{{cite web|title=Regulations for the Administration of Confucius Institute Headquarters Funds|url=http://english.hanban.org/article/2010-06/21/content_146458.htm|publisher=Hanban-News|accessdate=3 July 2011}}</ref> Institutes in the United States are generally provided with $100,000 annually from Hanban, with the local university required to match funding.<ref name=\"Schimdt 2010b\">Schimdt (2010b).</ref>\n\nIn addition to their local-partner university, Confucius Institutes operate in co-operation with a Chinese partner university.<ref>{{cite web|title=Confucius Institute at Tallinn University|url=http://www.tlu.ee/?LangID=2&CatID=5145|publisher=Tallinn University|accessdate=3 July 2011}}</ref> Many Institutes are governed by a board which is composed of several members from the Chinese partner school, with the remaining members affiliated with the local-partner university.<ref>{{cite web|title=Board of Directors|url=http://www.confuciusinstitute.buffalo.edu/people/board_of_directors/|publisher=University of Buffalo College of Arts and Sciences|accessdate=3 July 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120326130424/http://www.confuciusinstitute.buffalo.edu/people/board_of_directors/|archivedate=26 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}{{cite web|title=Governing and Advisory Boards|url=http://www.confucius.umn.edu/about/boards.html|publisher=Regents of the University of Minnesota|accessdate=3 July 2011}}{{cite web|title=Chinese language school in the world|url=https://www.cchatty.com/chineseschool/|publisher=Confucius Institute at the University of New South Wales|accessdate=3 July 2011}}</ref> At most Institutes, the director is appointed by the local partner university.<ref name=\"The Economist(2009)\" />\n\n==Hiring policy controversy==\nThe Hanban website stated that Chinese language instructors should be \"aged between 22 to 60, physical and mental healthy, no record of participation in [[Falun Gong]] and other illegal organizations, and no criminal record.\"<ref>Hanban, [http://www.chinese.cn/hanban_en/node_9806.htm \u2018Overseas Volunteer Chinese Teacher Program\u2019] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120122194907/http://www.chinese.cn/hanban_en/node_9806.htm |date=22 January 2012 }}. Retrieved 16 September 2011.</ref> In many universities, the employer is the Chinese government, not the university.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\nHuman rights lawyer Clive Ansley has argued that the part of the hiring policy that discriminates against Falun Gong believers is in contravention of anti-discrimination laws and human rights codes.<ref>Macleans, [http://oncampus.macleans.ca/education/2011/08/10/confucius-institutes-break-human-rights-rules/ Confucius Institutes break human rights rules:Profs working in Canada 'must have no record of Falun Gong'\"], 10 August 2011.</ref> Marci Hamilton, Paul R. Verkuil Chair in Public Law at [[Yeshiva University]], called this policy \"unethical and illegal in the free world.\"<ref name=Discrimination>Matthew Robertson, [http://www.theepochtimes.com/n2/united-states/at-us-universities-confucius-institutes-import-discrimination-60714.html\u201cAt US Universities, Confucius Institutes Import Discrimination\u201d], ''[[The Epoch Times]]'', 24 Aug 2011.{{unreliable source?|date=January 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, [[McMaster University]] in Canada closed its Confucius Institute due to hiring issues over Falun Gong.<ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/education/mcmaster-closing-confucius-institute-over-hiring-issues/article8372894/ McMaster closing Confucius Institute over hiring issues ], ''The Globe and Mail'', 7 February 2013.</ref>\n\n== Curriculum ==\nThe curriculum of Confucius Institutes is based on the institute's role as a language center.<ref name=\"econ\"/> Confucius Institutes teach [[simplified Chinese characters]], which are standard in Mainland China, rather than the [[traditional Chinese characters]] used in Taiwan and Hong Kong. Confucius Institutes provide a sanitized view of Chinese society which avoids contentious topics like [[human rights]] abuses and Tibet.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Power |first1=John |title=University of Queensland faces heat for naming Chinese diplomat Xu Jie as faculty member |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/asia/australasia/article/3019888/hong-kong-and-mainland-china-students-clash-rally-australian |website=www.scmp.com |publisher=South China Morning Post |accessdate=26 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Reception and controversies==\n{{Main|Criticism of Confucius Institutes}}\nIn the short time-frame of their rapid expansion, the Institutes have been the subject of much controversy. Criticisms of the Institutes have included administrative concerns about finance, academic viability, legal issues, and relations with the Chinese partner university, as well as broader concerns about improper influence over teaching and research, industrial and military espionage,<ref name=\"Michel Juneau-Katsuya 2009. pp 160\"/><ref name=\"canada.com\"/> surveillance of Chinese abroad, and undermining Taiwanese influence.<ref>Don Starr (2009), [http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1465-3435.2008.01371.x/full Chinese Language Education in Europe: the Confucius Institutes], ''European Journal of Education'' Volume 44, Issue 1, pages 78\u201379.</ref> There has also been organized opposition to the establishment of a Confucius Institute at [[University of Melbourne]],<ref>Geoff Maslen (2007), [http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=20071130094503100 Warning \u2013 be wary of Confucius institutes] University World News, 2 December 2007.</ref> [[University of Manitoba]],<ref>[http://oncampus.macleans.ca/education/2011/04/27/profs-worry-china-preparing-to-spy-on-students/ Profs worry China preparing to spy on students], ''Maclean's'', 27 April 2011.</ref> [[Stockholm University]],<ref>Starr (2009), p. 6.</ref><ref>\"i Kina \u00e4r tio miljoner barn utan en ordentlig skola\" [http://www.riksdagen.se/Webbnav/index.aspx?nid=101&bet=2007/08:46 Riksdagens snabbprotokoll 2007/08:46 (in Swedish)]</ref> [[University of Chicago]]<ref>Peter Schmidt (2010a), [http://chronicle.com/article/U-of-Chicagos-Plans-for-M/65737/ U. of Chicago's Plans for Milton Friedman Institute Stir Outrage on the Faculty], [[The Chronicle of Higher Education]], 1 June 2010.</ref> and many others. More significantly, some universities that hosted Confucius Institutes decided to terminate their contracts. These include Japan's [[Osaka Sangyo University]] in 2010;<ref>[http://english.peopledaily.com.cn/90001/90782/7023278.html Japanese university apologizes for calling Confucius Institute spy agency], ''People's Daily'', 12 June 2010.</ref> Canada's [[McMaster University]] and [[Universit\u00e9 de Sherbrooke]],<ref>James Bradshaw and Colin Freeze, [https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/education/mcmaster-closing-confucius-institute-over-hiring-issues/article8372894/ McMaster closing Confucius Institute over hiring issues], ''The Globe and Mail'', 7 February 2013.</ref><ref>Caroline Alphonso and Karen Howlett, [https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/toronto/toronto-school-board-seeks-end-to-china-deal/article19651681/ Toronto school board seeks end to China deal], ''The Globe and Mail'', 17 July 2014.</ref> and France's [[University of Lyon]] in 2013;<ref name=\"World should watch for Confucius\"/> the [[University of Chicago]], [[Pennsylvania State University]], and the [[Toronto District School Board]] in 2014,<ref name=\"insidehighered.com\">[https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2014/09/26/chicago-severs-ties-chinese-government-funded-confucius-institute Chicago to Close Confucius Institute], Inside Higher Ed, 26 September 2014</ref><ref>[http://www.la.psu.edu/news/confucius-institute-update Confucius Institute update], Penn State College of Liberal Arts, 1 October 2014.</ref><ref>[http://www.scmp.com/news/world/article/1628071/toronto-schools-reject-tie-chinas-confucius-institute Toronto schools reject tie-up with China\u2019s Confucius Institute], ''South China Morning Post'', 30 October 2014.</ref> the German [[Hochschule der Medien|Stuttgart Media University]] and [[University of Hohenheim]] in 2015,<ref>[https://www.insidehighered.com/quicktakes/2015/06/08/german-university-abandons-plans-confucius-institute German University Abandons Plans for Confucius Institute], ''Inside Higher Ed'', 8 June 2015.</ref><ref>[http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/13211073.Worldwide_campaign_launched_against_Confucius_Institutes/ Worldwide campaign launched against Confucius Institutes], ''The Sunday Herald'', 24 April 2015.</ref> and [[Vrije Universiteit Brussel]] in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tzu-ti |first1=Huang |title=Belgian university to shut down Confucius Institute |url=https://www.taiwannews.com.tw/en/news/3835636 |website=www.taiwannews.com.tw |publisher=Taiwan News |accessdate=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Criticism of Confucius Institutes|Controversy regarding Confucius Institutes]]  in the US, Australian, and Canadian press includes criticism that unlike other governments' language and culture promotion organizations, the Confucius Institutes operate within established universities, colleges, and secondary schools around the world, providing funding, teachers and educational materials.<ref name=ChinaU>{{cite news|last=Sahlins|first=Marshall|title=China U.|url=http://www.thenation.com/article/176888/china-u#|accessdate=11 April 2014|newspaper=The Nation|date=29 October 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Michel Juneau-Katsuya 2009. pp 160\" /><ref name=\"abc.net.au\">{{cite news|last1=Cohen|first1=Hagar|title=Australian universities the latest battleground in Chinese soft power offensive|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-10-14/universities-latest-battleground-in-chinese-soft-power-offensive/7931958|accessdate=13 October 2016|agency=ABC Australia}}</ref> This has raised concerns over their influence on academic freedom, the possibility of [[industrial espionage]],<ref>[http://www.canada.com/vancouversun/news/westcoastnews/story.html?id=179b4e77-f0cf-4608-a8b7-a9943116f489 'Has BCIT sold out to Chinese propaganda?'] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120822144124/http://www.canada.com/vancouversun/news/westcoastnews/story.html?id=179b4e77-f0cf-4608-a8b7-a9943116f489 |date=22 August 2012 }}, The Vancouver Sun, 2 April 2008.</ref> and concerns that the institutes present a selective and politicized view of China as a means of advancing the country's [[soft power]] internationally.<ref name=ChinaU/><ref name=\"abc.net.au\"/><ref>[http://www.economist.com/node/17969895 China's Confucius Institutes: Rectification of Statues], ''The Economist'',  20 January 2011.</ref>\n\nUnderlying such opposition is concern by professors that a Confucius Institute would interfere with academic freedom and be able to pressure the university to censor speech on topics the [[Communist Party of China]] objects to.<ref>{{cite news|last=Guttenplan|first=D. D.|title=Critics Worry About Influence of Chinese Institutes on U.S. Campuses|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/05/us/critics-worry-about-influence-of-chinese-institutes-on-us-campuses.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=4 March 2012|authorlink=D. D. Guttenplan}}</ref> An article in [[The Chronicle of Higher Education]] asserts that there is little evidence of meddling from China, although the same article did go on to say the Institutes were \"distinct in the degree to which they were financed and managed by a foreign government.\"<ref name=\"Schimdt 2010b\" /> After interviewing China scholars, journalists and CI directors, a writer for ''[[The Diplomat]]'' also found little support for the concern that CIs would serve as propaganda vehicles, though some of her sources did note that they would face constraints in their curriculum on matters such as Tibet and human rights.<ref>Ulara Nakagawa. [http://the-diplomat.com/new-emissary/2011/03/07/confucius-controversy/ Confucius Controversy], ''[[The Diplomat]]''.</ref> An article in ''[[The New York Times]]'' quotes [[Arthur Waldron]], a professor of international relations at the [[University of Pennsylvania]], saying that the key issue is academic independence. \"Once you have a Confucius Institute on campus, you have a second source of opinions and authority that is ultimately answerable to the Chinese Communist Party and which is not subject to scholarly review.\"<ref>[[D. D. Guttenplan]] (2012), [https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/05/us/critics-worry-about-influence-of-chinese-institutes-on-us-campuses.html Critics Worry About Influence of Chinese Institutes on U.S. Campuses], ''The New York Times'', 4 March 2012.</ref>\n\nIn October 2013, University of Chicago professor Marshall Sahlins published an extensive investigative article criticizing the Confucius Institutes and the universities hosting them.<ref name=\"thenation.com\">\"[http://www.thenation.com/article/176888/china-u China U: Confucius Institutes censor political discussions and restrain the free exchange of ideas. Why, then, do American universities sponsor them?]\" By Marshall Sahlins. The Nation, 18 November 2013</ref> Later, more than 100 faculty members signed a protest against the Confucius Institute at the University of Chicago.<ref>''[http://www.insidehighered.com/news/2014/04/29/chicago-faculty-object-their-campuss-confucius-institute#sthash.DFh0XAAH.dpbs Rejecting Confucius Funding]'' Inside Higher Ed, 29 April 2014. By Elizabeth Redden</ref> In September 2014, the University of Chicago suspended its negotiation for renewal of the agreement with Hanban.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://news.uchicago.edu/article/2014/09/25/statement-confucius-institute-university-chicago|title = Statement on the Confucius Institute at the University of Chicago|date = 25 September 2014|accessdate = 25 September 2014|website = UChicago News|publisher = University of Chicago}}</ref> Two months later, the Canadian Association of University Teachers urged Canadian universities and colleges to end ties with the Confucius Institute.<ref>''[http://www.caut.ca/news/2013/12/17/universities-and-colleges-urged-to-end-ties-with-confucius-institutes Universities and colleges urged to end ties with Confucius Institutes] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140820210709/http://www.caut.ca/news/2013/12/17/universities-and-colleges-urged-to-end-ties-with-confucius-institutes |date=20 August 2014 }}\" Canadian Association of University Teachers, 17 December 2013</ref>\n\nIn June 2014, the American Association of University Professors issued a statement urging American universities to cease their collaboration with the Confucius Institute unless the universities can have unilateral control of the academia affairs, that the teachers in Confucius Institutes can have the same academic freedom enjoyed by other university faculty members, and that the agreements between universities and Confucius Institutes are available to the community.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://aaup.org/report/partnerships-foreign-governments-case-confucius-institutes|title = Our Partnerships with Foreign Governments: The Case of Confucius Institutes|date = June 2014|accessdate = 21 June 2014|website = American Association of University Professors}}</ref> The AAUP statement was widely noticed by US media and prompted extensive further debate in the US.<ref>''[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/china/10907971/US-professors-urge-Western-universities-to-end-ties-to-Chinas-Confucius-Institutes.html US professors urge Western universities to end ties to China's Confucius Institutes]'' By Peter Foster, Washington. The Telegraph (London), 18 June 2014.</ref><ref>''[http://chronicle.com/article/AAUP-Rebukes-Colleges-for/147153/ AAUP Rebukes Colleges for Chinese Institutes, and Censures Northeastern Ill]'' Peter Schmidt, The Chronicle of Higher Education, 15 June 2014</ref><ref>''[https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/higher-education/us-professors-troubled-by-confucius-institutes/2014/06/23/d178eeba-fae5-11e3-9f27-09f20b8bfd1a_story.html US Professors Troubled by Confucius Institutes]'' Carolyn Thompson. 24 June 2014.</ref><ref>''[https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/the-price-of-confucius-institutes/2014/06/21/4d7598f2-f7b6-11e3-a3a5-42be35962a52_story.html The price of Confucius Institutes]'' Washington Post, Editorial Board 21 June 2014</ref>\n\nTwo months later, in August 2014, Xu Lin, Director-General of the Hanban and Chief Executive of the CIs worldwide, became embroiled in an [[Braga Incident|incident in Braga, Portugal]], when Xu ordered her staff to rip pages referring to Taiwanese academic institutions from the published program for the [[European Association for Chinese Studies]] conference in [[Braga]], claiming the materials were \"contrary to Chinese regulations\".<ref name=\"China's Soft-Power Fail\">[http://www.bloombergview.com/articles/2014-10-07/china-s-soft-power-fail China's Soft-Power Fail], Bloomberg View, 7 October 2014.</ref> ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' described Xu's attempted censorship as the \"bullying approach to academic freedom\".<ref name=\"online.wsj.com\">[https://www.wsj.com/articles/beijings-propaganda-lessons-1407430440 Beijing's Propaganda Lessons: Confucius Institute officials are agents of Chinese censorship], The Wall Street Journal, 7 August 2014.</ref>\n\nIn September 2014, the [[University of Chicago]] closed their CI after pressure from faculty members, blaming Xu's comments that her threatening letter and phone call forced the university to continue hosting the institute.<ref name=\"insidehighered.com\"/><ref name=Redden>{{cite web|last1=Redden|first1=Elizabeth|title=Chicago to Close Confucius Institute|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2014/09/26/chicago-severs-ties-chinese-government-funded-confucius-institute|publisher=[[Inside Higher Ed]]|accessdate=28 September 2014}}</ref> The ''[[Business Spectator]]'' concludes that the Xu Lin's hardline behavior highlights one of the biggest problems for Beijing's charm offensive. \"It still relies on officials like Xu, who still think and act like party ideologues who like to assert their authority and bully people into submission.\"<ref>[http://www.businessspectator.com.au/article/2014/9/29/china/hard-times-chinas-soft-power Hard times for China's soft power], Business Spectator, 29 September 2014.</ref> Less than a week later, [[Pennsylvania State University]] also cut ties with the Confucius Institute after coming to the conclusion that \"its objectives were not in line with the Institute's\".<ref name=\"Belkin, Douglas\">{{cite news |url = https://www.wsj.com/articles/penn-state-latest-school-to-drop-chinas-confucius-institute-1412196655|title = Penn State Latest School to Drop China's Confucius Institute|work = The Wall Street Journal|date = 1 October 2014|accessdate = 3 October 2014|author = Belkin, Douglas}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2014, [[Stockholm University]], the first university in Europe to host a Confucius Institute, announced it was terminating the program. Press coverage of the [[Braga incident]] in the Swedish press was said to have influenced the decision. \"Generally it is questionable to have, within the framework of the university, institutes that are financed by another country,\" said the university's chancellor.<ref>[https://networks.h-net.org/node/22055/discussions/56521/stockholm-university-terminating-its-confucius-institute Stockholm University terminating its Confucius Institute]</ref>\n\nIn the same month, the [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on Africa, Global Health, Global Human Rights and International Organizations]] held a hearing entitled \"Is Academic Freedom Threatened by China's Influence on U.S. Universities?\".<ref>[http://foreignaffairs.house.gov/hearing/subcommittee-hearing-academic-freedom-threatened-chinas-influence-us-universities Subcommittee Hearing: Is Academic Freedom Threatened by China's Influence on U.S. Universities?], House Committee on Foreign Affairs, 4 December 2014.</ref> Chairman [[Chris Smith (New Jersey politician)|Chris Smith]] said, \"U.S. colleges and universities should not be outsourcing academic control, faculty and student oversight or curriculum to a foreign government\", and called for a [[Government Accountability Office|GAO]] study into agreements between American universities and China.<ref>[http://www.latimes.com/nation/la-na-chinese-influence-20141205-story.html China's influence threatens American universities, experts say], ''Los Angeles Times'', 4 December 2014.</ref> On 5 December 2014, PRC [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the People's Republic of China|Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] spokeswoman [[Hua Chunying]] denied the House testimony and said \"We have assisted with supplying teachers and textbooks at the request of the U.S. side but have never interfered with academic freedom.\"<ref>[https://blogs.wsj.com/chinarealtime/2014/12/05/china-says-its-never-interfered-with-u-s-academic-freedom/ China Says It\u2019s 'Never Interfered With U.S. Academic Freedom'], Chinarealtime, ''The Wall Street Journal'', 5 December 2014.</ref>\n\nControversy continued in 2018 as U.S. Congress members from [[Texas]] wrote a letter to four universities in that state urging them to close their Confucius Institutes.  [[Texas A&M]] did so shortly after receiving the letter.<ref name=2018_Texas_AM_closure>{{Cite web |url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2018/04/09/texas-am-cuts-ties-confucius-institutes-response-congressmens-concerns |title=Closing a Confucius Institute, at Congressmen's Request |author=Elizabeth Redden |date=April 9, 2018 |accessdate=April 9, 2018}}</ref> Throughout 2018 and 2019, all of the institutes in TFlorida were closed: the [[University of West Florida]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/quicktakes/2018/02/06/more-scrutiny-confucius-institutes-one-close|title=More Scrutiny for Confucius Institutes; One to Close {{!}} Inside Higher Ed|website=www.insidehighered.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> the [[University of North Florida]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/quicktakes/2018/08/16/north-florida-will-close-confucius-institute|title=North Florida Will Close Confucius Institute|last=Redden|first=Elizabeth|date=Aug 16, 2018|work=Inside Higher Ed|access-date=Jan 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>, the [[University of South Florida]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2019/01/09/colleges-move-close-chinese-government-funded-confucius-institutes-amid-increasing|title=Colleges move to close Chinese government-funded Confucius Institutes amid increasing scrutiny|website=www.insidehighered.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> and [[Miami Dade College]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://politi.co/2zUofIt|title=Miami Dade College is shutting down its Confucius Institute|last=Andrew Atterbury|website=Politico PRO|language=en|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref>\n\nA U.S. law passed in 2019 that prohibits universities hosting Confucius Institutes from receiving funding for Chinese language studies from the Department of Defense led to more closures of Confucius Institutes. Unable to obtained a waiver from the Department of Defense, [[Indiana University]], the [[University of Minnesota]], the [[University of Rhode Island]], [[San Francisco State University]], the [[University of Oregon]], [[Western Kentucky University]], [[Arizona State University]], the [[University of Hawaii at Manoa]], and [[San Diego State University]] closed their the programs in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/quicktakes/2019/05/01/3-more-universities-close-confucius-institutes|title=3 More Universities Close Confucius Institutes {{!}} Inside Higher Ed|website=www.insidehighered.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.chronicle.com/article/Another-Confucius-Institute/247025|title=Another Confucius Institute Closes|last=Fischer|first=Karin|date=2019-08-28|work=The Chronicle of Higher Education|access-date=2020-01-20|language=en-US|issn=0009-5982}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2019/07/29/hawaii-news/university-of-hawaiis-confucius-institute-closes-as-fbi-raises-alarm/|title=University of Hawaii's Confucius Institute closes as FBI raises alarm|last=wcole@staradvertiser.com|first=By William Cole|last2=July 29|first2=2019|date=2019-07-29|website=Honolulu Star-Advertiser|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/asian-america/u-s-colleges-face-tough-choice-take-money-china-lose-n1055871|title=U.S. colleges face tough choice: Take money from China and lose federal funding|website=NBC News|language=en|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> In 2020, the [[University of Maryland]] also announced the closure of its Confucius Institute, the oldest one in the U.S..<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wamu.org/story/20/01/17/following-federal-pressure-umd-will-close-a-program-that-had-chinese-government-support/|title=Following Federal Pressure, UMD Will Close A Program That Had Chinese Government Support|website=WAMU|language=en|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> \n\nOn 19 February 2019, [[Leiden University]] in The Netherlands promised to end its agreement with Confucius Institute in August 2019. <ref name=\"2019_Leiden\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.universiteitleiden.nl/en/news/2019/02/confusius-instituut-en|title=Leiden University to end agreement with Confucius Institute |date=February 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Chinese Bridge]]\n*[[Istituto Italiano di Cultura]]\n*[[Dante Alighieri Society]]\n*[[Goethe-Institut]]\n*[[Instituto Cam\u00f5es]]\n*[[Instituto Cervantes]]\n*[[Institut Fran\u00e7ais]]\n*China's \"[[Propaganda in the People's Republic of China#Soft power initiative|soft power initiative]]\"\n*[[Propaganda in the People's Republic of China]]\n*[[Panda diplomacy]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Biswas, Asit K., and Kris Hartley. \"China\u2019s soft power struggles.\" ''Asia and the Pacific Policy Society'' (2017). [https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Asit_Biswas/publication/320961581_China's_soft_power_struggles/links/5a04b49c0f7e9bc4078ecc5e/Chinas-soft-power-struggles.pdf online]\n* Callahan, William A. \"Identity and security in China: the negative soft power of the China dream.\" ''Politics'' 35.3-4 (2015): 216-229. [http://eprints.lse.ac.uk/64455/1/__lse.ac.uk_storage_LIBRARY_Secondary_libfile_shared_repository_Content_Callahan,%20W_Identity%20and%20security_Callahan_Identity%20and%20security_2015.pdf online]\n* Hubbert, Jennifer. ''China in the World: An Anthropology of Confucius Institutes, Soft Power, and Globalization'' (University of Hawai\u2018i Press, 2019) . viii + 234 pp.  [https://www.h-net.org/reviews/showpdf.php?id=54259 online scholarly review]\n* Lahtinen, Anja. \"China's soft power: Challenges of Confucianism and Confucius Institutes.\" ''Journal of Comparative Asian Development'' 14.2 (2015): 200-226. [https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Anja_Lahtinen/publication/282204244_China%27s_Soft_Power_Challenges_of_Confucianism_and_Confucius_Institutes/links/5addd5e90f7e9b285941aa66/Chinas-Soft-Power-Challenges-of-Confucianism-and-Confucius-Institutes.pdf online]\n* Peterson, Rachelle. ''Outsourced to China: Confucius Institutes and Soft Power in American Higher Education. A Report by the National Association of Scholars.'' (National Association of Scholars. 2017). [https://files.eric.ed.gov/fulltext/ED580866.pdf online]\n* Procopio, Maddalena. \"The effectiveness of Confucius Institutes as a tool of China\u2019s soft power in South Africa.\" ''African East-Asian Affairs'' 1-2 (2015). [http://aeaa.journals.ac.za/pub/article/download/155/111  online]\n* Tella, Oluwaseun. \"Wielding soft power in strategic regions: an analysis of China\u2019s power of attraction in Africa and the Middle East.\" ''Africa Review'' 8.2 (2016): 133-144. [https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/09744053.2016.1186868 online]\n* Zhou, Ying, and Sabrina Luk. \"Establishing Confucius Institutes: a tool for promoting China\u2019s soft power?.\" ''Journal of Contemporary China'' 25.100 (2016): 628-642.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Confucius Institute}}\n{{Library resources box}}\n*[http://www.chinesecio.com/ Confucius Institute Online] {{in lang|zh}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20061209220936/http://english.hanban.edu.cn/ China National Office for Teaching Chinese as a Foreign Language] {{in lang|zh}}\n*[http://confuciusinstitute.unl.edu/institutes.shtml List of Confucius Institutes around the world]\n* Pella, John & Erik Ringmar, \"[http://www.irhistory.info/index.php/confucius-and-the-jesuits Kongzi and his institutes],\" ''History of International Relations Open Textbook Project,'' Cambridge: Open Book, forthcoming.\n*[https://www.youtube.com/user/pricklyparadigmtv Sahlins on Confucius Institutes], four-part lecture by [[Marshall Sahlins]], PricklyParadigmTV, YouTube.\n*[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-30567743 Confucius institute: The hard side of China's soft power], Xu Lin interview, BBC News, 21 December 2014.\n\n{{International cultural promotion organizations}}\n\n[[Category:Chinese-language education]]\n[[Category:Confucius]]\n[[Category:Confucius Institute| ]]\n[[Category:Cultural promotion organizations]]\n[[Category:Foreign relations of China]]\n[[Category:Language advocacy organizations]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 2004]]\n[[Category:Sinology]]\n[[Category:2004 establishments in China]]\n[[Category:Organizations associated with the Communist Party of China]]\n", "name_user": "Anas1712", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFurther reading:Insert templates to bare references", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confucius_Institute"}
{"title_page": "Government Engineering College, Vaishali", "text_new": "{{moresources|date=February 2020}}\n{{short description|Government engineering college in Hajipur, Bihar}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name = Government Engineering College, Vaishali\n| native_name = \n| image = Government Engineering College, Vaishali Logo.png\n| caption = \n| established = 2018\n| type = Government Engineering college\n| motto = \n| principal = Dr. Anant Kumar\n| chairman = \n| undergrad = \n| staff = 15\n| faculty = 30\n| free_label = GECV\n| free = \n| students = 420\n| city = [[Vaishali district|Vaishali]]\n| state = [[Bihar]]\n| country = [[India]]\n| campus = Rural\n| colors = \n| nickname = GEC Vaishali\n| affiliations = [[Aryabhatta Knowledge University]]\n| website = {{URL|https://www.gecvaishali.org/}}\n| logo = \n}}\n'''Government Engineering College, Vaishali''' ('''GEC Vaishali''') is a technical institute established in 2018 by the [[Government of Bihar]] under the [[Department of Science and Technology, Bihar]].<ref>http://dst.bih.nic.in</ref> It is approved by [[All India Council for Technical Education|AICTE]] and is affiliated with [[Aryabhatta Knowledge University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://akubihar.ac.in/Colleges/Engineering.aspx|title=.:Official Website : Aryabhatta Knowledge University, Patna:.|website=akubihar.ac.in|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref> The institute offers full-time [[Bachelor of Technology]] (B.Tech) degree programs. It started its first academic session(2018\u201319) in temporary campus from the campus of Government Polytechnic College, Vaishali. It is also popularly known as IIT Vaishali. The institute offers full-time [[Bachelor of Technology]] (B.Tech) degree programs in disciplines of science and technology. The Permanent building is to be built by February 2020 near Bidupur, Hajipur, Vaishali.  \n\n== Departments ==\nGEC Vaishali offers undergraduate courses in four streams of engineering:\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Departmental Courses in B.Tech. offered\n!Intake and seats available\n|-\n|B.Tech. [[Electronics and Communication engineering|Electronics and Communication Engineering]]\n|60 (Normal Entry Seats)\n|-\n|B.Tech. [[Electrical engineering|Electrical Engineering]]\n|60 (Normal Entry Seats)\n|-\n|B.Tech. [[Mechanical engineering|Mechanical Engineering]]\n|60 (Normal Entry Seats) \n|-\n|B.Tech. [[Civil Engineering]]\n|60 (Normal Entry Seats)\n|}\n\n== Admission ==\nTill 2018: The Bihar Combined Entrance Competitive Examination Board<ref>http://bceceboard.bihar.gov.in</ref>(BCECEB) conducts an exam based on the Merit List of the Bihar Combined Entrance Competitive Examination  successful candidates appear in the counseling at the allotted college during online counseling procedure\n\nFrom 2019 onwards admissions in state engineering colleges of Bihar will be based on [[Joint Entrance Examination \u2013 Main|JEE mains]] rank. Students have to fill the application form on the BCECE Board website for admission.\n\n== Campus and location ==\nGEC Vaishali Temporary campus is located at ''Government Polytechnic Campus, Fatehpur, Afzalpur Road, Pochakmaruf, Goraul, Vaishali, Bihar \u2013 844118''. Permanent campus to built by February 2020 at Bidupur, Hajipur, Vaishali\n\n== College facilities ==\n* College Library\n* Different clubs for student\n** \n* Computer LAB\n* Anti-ragging committee\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Education|Engineering|India}}\n* [[List of institutions of higher education in Bihar]]\n* [[Aryabhatta Knowledge University]]\n* [[Education in Patna]]\n* [[Education in Bihar]]\n* [[Education in India]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official|https://www.gecvaishali.org/}}\n*[https://www.facebook.com/Gecvaishali/ Facebook page]\n*[https://www.instagram.com/gecvaishali/ Instagram Profile]\n\n{{Aryabhatta Knowledge University}}\n{{Engineering Colleges in Bihar}}\n{{coord missing|Bihar}}\n\n[[Category:Engineering colleges in Vaishali]]\n[[Category:Colleges affiliated to Aryabhatta Knowledge University]]\n[[Category:Engineering colleges in Bihar]]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vaishali}}\n", "text_old": "{{moresources|date=February 2020}}\n{{short description|Government engineering college in Hajipur, Bihar}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name = Government Engineering College, Vaishali\n| native_name = \n| image = Government Engineering College, Vaishali Logo.png\n| caption = \n| established = 2018\n| type = Government Engineering college\n| motto = \n| principal = Dr. Anant Kumar\n| chairman = \n| undergrad = \n| staff = 15\n| faculty = 30\n| free_label = GECV\n| free = \n| students = 420\n| city = [[Vaishali district|Vaishali]]\n| state = [[Bihar]]\n| country = [[India]]\n| campus = Rural\n| colors = \n| nickname = GEC Vaishali\n| affiliations = [[Aryabhatta Knowledge University]]\n| website = {{URL|https://www.gecvaishali.org/}}\n| logo = \n}}\n'''Government Engineering College, Vaishali''' ('''GEC Vaishali''') is a technical institute established in 2018 by the [[Government of Bihar]] under the [[Department of Science and Technology, Bihar]].<ref>http://dst.bih.nic.in</ref> It is approved by [[All India Council for Technical Education|AICTE]] and is affiliated with [[Aryabhatta Knowledge University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://akubihar.ac.in/Colleges/Engineering.aspx|title=.:Official Website : Aryabhatta Knowledge University, Patna:.|website=akubihar.ac.in|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref> The institute offers full-time [[Bachelor of Technology]] (B.Tech) degree programs. It started its first academic session(2018\u201319) in temporary campus from the campus of Government Polytechnic College, Vaishali. It is also popularly known as IIT Vaishali.  \n\nThe institute offers full-time [[Bachelor of Technology]] (B.Tech) degree programs in disciplines of science and technology: College offers B.Tech in four branches: Electronics & Communication Engineering, Electrical Engineering, Mechanical Engineering, and Civil Engineering. The Permanent building is to be built by February 2020 near Bidupur, Hajipur, Vaishali. \n\n== Departments ==\nGEC Vaishali offers undergraduate courses in four streams of engineering:\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Departmental Courses in B.Tech. offered\n!Intake and seats available\n|-\n|B.Tech. [[Electronics and Communication engineering|Electronics and Communication Engineering]]\n|60 (Normal Entry Seats)\n|-\n|B.Tech. [[Electrical engineering|Electrical Engineering]]\n|60 (Normal Entry Seats)\n|-\n|B.Tech. [[Mechanical engineering|Mechanical Engineering]]\n|60 (Normal Entry Seats) \n|-\n|B.Tech. [[Civil Engineering]]\n|60 (Normal Entry Seats)\n|}\n\n== Admission ==\nTill 2018: The Bihar Combined Entrance Competitive Examination Board<ref>http://bceceboard.bihar.gov.in</ref>(BCECEB) conducts an exam based on the Merit List of the Bihar Combined Entrance Competitive Examination  successful candidates appear in the counseling at the allotted college during online counseling procedure\n\nFrom 2019 onwards admissions in state engineering colleges of Bihar will be based on [[Joint Entrance Examination \u2013 Main|JEE mains]] rank. Students have to fill the application form on the BCECE Board website for admission.\n\n== Campus and location ==\nGEC Vaishali Temporary campus is located at ''Government Polytechnic Campus, Fatehpur, Afzalpur Road, Pochakmaruf, Goraul, Vaishali, Bihar \u2013 844118''. Permanent campus to built by February 2020 at Bidupur, Hajipur, Vaishali\n\n== College facilities ==\n* College Library\n* Different clubs for student\n** \n* Computer LAB\n* Anti-ragging committee\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Education|Engineering|India}}\n* [[List of institutions of higher education in Bihar]]\n* [[Aryabhatta Knowledge University]]\n* [[Education in Patna]]\n* [[Education in Bihar]]\n* [[Education in India]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official|https://www.gecvaishali.org/}}\n*[https://www.facebook.com/Gecvaishali/ Facebook page]\n*[https://www.instagram.com/gecvaishali/ Instagram Profile]\n\n{{Aryabhatta Knowledge University}}\n{{Engineering Colleges in Bihar}}\n{{coord missing|Bihar}}\n\n[[Category:Engineering colleges in Vaishali]]\n[[Category:Colleges affiliated to Aryabhatta Knowledge University]]\n[[Category:Engineering colleges in Bihar]]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vaishali}}\n", "name_user": "Geekvinish", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Government_Engineering_College,_Vaishali"}
{"title_page": "Whitefoord Russell Cole", "text_new": "{{Infobox person \n| name = Whiteford Russell Cole\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = January 14, 1874\n| birth_place = [[Nashville, Tennessee]], U.S.\n| death_date = November 17, 1934 (aged 60)\n| death_place = [[Cave City, Kentucky]], U.S.\n| resting_place = Nashville, Tennessee, U.S.\n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| residence = 2122 West End Avenue, Nashville, Tennessee, U.S.<br/>2515 Longest Avenue, [[Louisville, Kentucky]], U.S.\n| nationality = \n| other_names = \n| known_for = \n| education = Wallace University Prep School\n| alma mater= [[Vanderbilt University]]\n| employer = \n| occupation = Businessman\n| title = \n| salary = \n| networth = $600,000 <small>(1934)</small><ref name=\"courierjournalcolewill\"/>\n| term = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| party = \n| boards = \n| religion = \n| spouse = Mary Conner Bass\n| children = 1\n| parents = [[Edmund William Cole]]<br/>Anna Russell\n| relatives = [[John Trotwood Moore]] <small>(daughter-in-law's father)</small>\n| box_width = \n}}\n'''Whiteford Russell Cole''' (January 14, 1874 \u2013 November 17, 1934) was an American businessman. He was the president of the [[Louisville and Nashville Railroad]] from 1926 to 1934, and a director of many companies. During the railroad [[strike action]]s of 1921\u20131922, he threatened his workers with dismissal and loss of pensions. His mansion in [[Louisville, Kentucky]] is the official residence of the president of the [[University of Louisville]].\n\n==Early life==\nWhiteford Russell Cole was born on January 14, 1874, in [[Nashville, Tennessee]].<ref name=\"stlouisdispatchobituary\">{{cite news|title=L. & N. PRESIDENT, W. R. COLE, DIES; STRICKEN ON TRAIN. On Way Home to Louisville After Consulting Doctor When End Comes\u201460 Years Old.|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/139037786/?terms=%22Whitefoord%2BRussell%2BCole%22|work=St. Louis Post-Dispatch|date=November 18, 1934|page=1|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url-access=registration }}</ref><ref name=\"tennesseanwillbeburied\">{{cite news|title=WHITEFORD COLE WILL BE BURIED IN NASHVILLE TODAY. Special Train to Bring Body for Service.|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/172725641/?terms=%22Whitefoord%2BR.%2BCole%22|accessdate=October 25, 2017|work=The Tennessean|date=November 19, 1934|pages=1; 3|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url-access=registration }}</ref><ref name=\"tennesseanwhitefoodchosen18\">{{cite news|title=WHITEFORD COLE CHOSEN TO HEAD N., C. & ST. L. R. R.. Local Capitalist Elected to Succeed John H. Peyton as President. SAME PLACE FILLED BY FATHER FIFTY YEARS AGO. T. R. Preston and Walker Keith Elected to Vacancies in Directorate.|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/119345349|accessdate=October 27, 2017|work=The Tennessean|date=October 9, 1918|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url-access=registration |pages=1; 10}}</ref> His father, [[Edmund William Cole]], was a Confederate veteran and railroad executive; his mother, Anna Russell, was a philanthropist.<ref name=\"tennesseanwhitefoodchosen18\"/><ref name=\"jstorannerussellcoleastudyof\">{{cite journal|last1=Burt|first1=Jesse C., Jr.|title=Anna Russell Cole: A Study of a Grande Dame|journal=Tennessee Historical Quarterly|date=June 1954|volume=13|issue=2|pages=127\u2013155|jstor=42621182}}</ref> His maternal uncle, Whitefoord Russell, was a Confederate veteran, and his maternal great-uncle was a professor at the [[University of Georgia]] and [[Berlin University]].<ref name=\"jstorannerussellcoleastudyof\"/> Cole grew up at [[Colemere]], a mansion in Nashville, with three half-siblings from his father's first marriage to a member of the McGavock family; his parents entertained often.<ref name=\"jstorannerussellcoleastudyof\"/>\n\nCole was educated at the Wallace University Prep School.<ref name=\"courierjournalheadofroad\">{{cite news|title=HEAD OF ROAD SUCCUMBS IN PRIVATE CAR. Business Leader Was Returning to Louisville From Nashville. CHIEF OF LINE 8 YEARS. Porter Stops Train, Calls Doctor, Who Finds Executive Dead.|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/107507237/?terms=%22Whitefoord%2BR.%2BCole%22|accessdate=October 25, 2017|work=The Courier-Journal|date=November 18, 1934|location=Louisville, Kentucky|page=2|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url-access=registration }}</ref> He graduated from [[Vanderbilt University]] in 1894.<ref name=\"tennesseanwhitefoodchosen18\"/><ref name=\"tnportrait\">{{cite web|title=Whitefoord Russell Cole 1874 \u2013 1934|url=http://tnportraits.org/cole-whitefoord-russell.htm|website=Tennessee Portrait Project|publisher=National Society of Colonial Dames of America in Tennessee|accessdate=October 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nCole was appointed as a director of the [[Nashville, Chattanooga and St. Louis Railway]] at the age of 26, in 1900.<ref name=\"stlouisdispatchobituary\"/> He had become its chairman by the outset of World War I,<ref name=\"stlouisdispatchobituary\"/> and he was appointed as its president in 1918.<ref name=\"filsonclubarticle\"/><ref name=\"tennesseanwhitefoodchosen18\"/> In 1919, he opposed [[Director General of Railroads]] [[William Gibbs McAdoo]]'s proposal to [[Nationalization|nationalize]] railroads for five years, arguing that \"debts would pile so high that it would be physically impossible for the roads to ever again revert to private ownership\".<ref name=\"rotariansopposed4\">{{cite news|title=ROTARIANS ARE OPPOSED TO U.S. RAIL CONTROL. Whitefoord Cole Says Debts Would Swamp Roads in Five-Year Period.|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/119394020/?terms=%22Whitefoord%2BCole%22|accessdate=October 27, 2017|work=The Tennessean|date=January 29, 1919|page=4|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url-access=registration }}</ref> In 1921\u20131922, when his railroad workers went on strike after their wages were lowered by 12 percent by the [[Railroad Labor Board|U.S. Railway Labor Board]], Cole threatened them with dismissal and loss of their pensions.<ref name=\"filsonclubarticle\"/><ref name=\"tennesseeanboardmeetsrailand\">{{cite news|title=BOARD MEETS RAIL AND \"BIG FIVE\" CHIEFS TODAY. Whitefoord R. Cole, President of N., C. & St. L., Appeals to Employees on His Road. Asks Men to Consider Situation Well Before Deciding to Walk Out on October 30.|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/118940592|accessdate=25 October 2017|work=The Tennessean|date=October 26, 1921|pages=1; 10|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url-access=registration }}</ref> In retaliation, strikers went to his house on West End Avenue, and they \"bombarded [it] with bottles until its concrete porch was littered with glass\".<ref name=\"filsonclubarticle\"/> In 1923, Cole dedicated the Whitefoord Cole Park in [[Murfreesboro, Tennessee]], for use by residents even though it belonged to the company.<ref name=\"tennesseanmurfreesboropark\">{{cite news|title=Murfreesboro Park Will Be Dedicated|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/178412876/?terms=%22Whitefoord%2BCole%22|accessdate=October 26, 2017|work=The Tennessean|date=July 24, 1923|page=2|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url-access=registration }}</ref> Cole resigned in 1926.<ref name=\"instepwith\">{{cite news|title=L. & N. HEAD IN STEP WITH SOUTH'S GROWTH. PRODUCTS SHOWS BIG INCREASE. Whitefoord R. Cole Cites Figures on Rail Shipments to Show Development. SOLD IN SOUTH. Rail Magnate Also Devotes Time To Vanderbilt University, Heading Board.|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/178891730/?terms=%22Whitefoord%2BR.%2BCole%22|accessdate=October 27, 2017|work=The Tennessean|date=October 30, 1927|page=35|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url-access=registration }}</ref>\n\nCole was the president of the [[Louisville and Nashville Railroad]] from 1926 to 1934.<ref name=\"instepwith\"/><ref name=\"stlouisdispatchobituary\"/><ref name=\"filsonclubarticle\">{{cite journal|last1=Burt|first1=Jesse C., Jr|title=Whitefoord Russell Cole: A Study in Character|journal=[[The Filson Club History Quarterly]]|date=January 1954|volume=28|pages=28\u201348}}</ref> At the time of his appointment, [[B. C. Forbes]], the founder of ''[[Forbes]]'' magazine, noted that it was unusual for a man of privileged upbringing to become the president of a railroad company.<ref name=\"philadelphiainquirerrichboyhaschance\">{{cite news|last1=Forbes|first1=B. C.|title=RICH BOY HAS CHANCE IN THE UNITED STATES. When He Buckles Down to Work With Determination to Win Wealth Is Not An Insurmountable Obstacle; New President of Louisville and Nashville Proves an Example|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/173520100/?terms=%22Whitefoord%2BR.%2BCole%22|work=The Philadelphia Inquirer|date=June 1, 1926|page=32|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url-access=registration }}</ref> As it was the [[Great Depression]], Cole lowered his workers' wages and took a pay cut.<ref name=\"filsonclubarticle\"/>\n\nCole was the president and general manager of the Napier Iron Works and vice president of the First Savings Bank & Trust Company and the Bransford Realty Company.<ref name=\"tennesseanwhitefoodchosen18\"/> He also served on the boards of directors of First and Fourth National Bank, Nashville Trust Company,<ref name=\"tennesseanwhitefoodchosen18\"/> the [[Western Railway of Alabama]],<ref name=\"stlouisdispatchobituary\"/> the [[Monon Railroad]], the Southern Bell Telephone & Telegraph Company, the American Nashville Bank of Nashville, [[American Cyanamid]], [[Fruit Growers Express]] and Fidelity & Columbia Trust Company.<ref name=\"courierjournalheadofroad\"/> He was a member of the [[Association of American Railroads]].<ref name=\"courierjournalheadofroad\"/>\n\nCole was a significant real estate investor in [[Sheffield, Alabama]].<ref name=\"thetennesseanonehundredhouses\">{{cite news|title=ONE HUNDRED HOUSES. Whitefoord Cole May Erect Them at Sheffield.|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/118842107/?terms=%22Whitefoord%2BCole%22|accessdate=October 27, 2017|work=The Tennessean|date=March 25, 1902|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url-access=registration |page=2}}</ref>\n\n==Civic activities and politics==\nCole served on the board of trustees of the [[Brookings Institution]].<ref name=\"stlouisdispatchobituary\"/> He served on the board of trustees of the Tennessee Industrial School, founded by his father, and the [[University School of Nashville]].<ref name=\"tennesseanwhitefoodchosen18\"/> He was also the chairman of the board of trust of his alma mater, Vanderbilt University, from 1915 to 1934.<ref name=\"tnportrait\"/> He supported chancellor [[James Hampton Kirkland]]'s decision to split with the [[Methodist Church]].<ref name=\"filsonclubarticle\"/> He served on the board of missions of the [[Methodist Episcopal Church, South]]<ref name=\"tennesseanwhitefoodchosen18\"/> until he joined the Episcopal Church, possibly as a return of the split.<ref name=\"filsonclubarticle\"/>\n\nCole was a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]].<ref name=\"rotariansopposed4\"/> According to ''[[The Tennessean]]'', he was opposed to \"any move that made for a greater centralization of governmental power than was necessary to perform its proper functions\".<ref name=\"rotariansopposed4\"/> He was a critic of [[laissez-faire capitalism]] as well as [[communism]].<ref name=\"filsonclubarticle\"/>\n\n==Personal life, death and legacy==\nCole married Mary Conner Bass, a direct descendant of [[Felix Grundy]], in 1901.<ref name=\"filsonclubarticle\"/> They had a son, Whitefoord Russell Cole, Jr.,<ref name=\"filsonclubarticle\"/> who married Helen Lane Moore, the daughter of State Historian and Archivist [[John Trotwood Moore]] and sister of poet [[Merrill Moore]].<ref name=\"courierjournalheadofroad\"/> They resided at 2122 West End Avenue, which was later repurposed as the Nashville Conservatory of Music.<ref name=\"tennesseanwillbeburied\"/> In 1926, they moved to 2515 Longest Avenue in [[Louisville, Kentucky]] (now known as Amelia Place, the official resident of the president of the [[University of Louisville]]).<ref name=\"tennesseanwillbeburied\"/><ref name=\"eventcalendarlouisville\">{{cite web|title=Event Calendar: Amelia Place|url=http://events.louisville.edu/amelia_place#.We_c9RNSzBI|website=University of Louisville|accessdate=October 25, 2017}}</ref> Cole was a member of the Nashville Golf and Country Club, the [[Pendennis Club]], the Louisville Country Club, and the [[Salmagundi Club]].<ref name=\"courierjournalheadofroad\"/>\n\nCole died of [[Cardiovascular disease|heart disease]] on November 17, 1934 on a train in [[Cave City, Kentucky]].<ref name=\"stlouisdispatchobituary\"/> He was 60 years old.<ref name=\"stlouisdispatchobituary\"/> His funeral was held at the [[Christ Church Cathedral (Nashville, Tennessee)|Christ Church Cathedral]],<ref name=\"tennesseanwillbeburied\"/> and he was buried in Nashville.<ref name=\"courierjournalheadofroad\"/> By the time of his death, he was worth an estimated $600,000.<ref name=\"courierjournalcolewill\">{{cite news|title=COLE WILL DISPOSES OF $600,000 ESTATE|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/107507767/?terms=%22Whitefoord%2BR.%2BCole%22|accessdate=October 25, 2017|work=The Courier-Journal|date=November 27, 1934|location=Louisville, Kentucky|page=4|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url-access=registration }}</ref> His estate was split between his wife and his son (whose trust fund would become available at age 30).<ref name=\"courierjournalcolewill\"/> Cole also bequeathed money to the Christ Church cathedrals in Nashville and [[Christ Church Cathedral (Louisville, Kentucky)|Louisville]].<ref name=\"courierjournalcolewill\"/>\n\nCole Hall, a building on the Vanderbilt campus completed in 1949, was named in his honor.<ref name=\"tnportrait\"/> Additionally, his portrait hangs in Kirkland Hall, the administration building;<ref name=\"tnportrait\"/> it was donated by his son in 1958.<ref name=\"portraitgiven\">{{cite news|title=Whitefood Cole, Sr., Portrait Given by Son to Vanderbilt|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/107767686/?terms=%22Whitefoord%2BRussell%2BCole%22|work=The Courier-Journal|date=January 16, 1958|location=Louisville, Kentucky|page=15|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url-access=registration }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cole, Whitefoord Russell}}\n[[Category:1874 births]]\n[[Category:1934 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Nashville, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:People from Louisville, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Vanderbilt University alumni]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Kentucky]]\n[[Category:American corporate directors]]\n[[Category:University of Louisville people]]\n[[Category:Louisville and Nashville Railroad people]]\n[[Category:Kentucky Democrats]]\n[[Category:Tennessee Democrats]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person \n| name = Whiteford Russell Cole\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = January 14, 1874\n| birth_place = [[Nashville, Tennessee]], U.S.\n| death_date = November 17, 1934 (aged 60)\n| death_place = [[Cave City, Kentucky]], U.S.\n| resting_place = Nashville, Tennessee, U.S.\n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| residence = 2122 West End Avenue, Nashville, Tennessee, U.S.<br/>2515 Longest Avenue, [[Louisville, Kentucky]], U.S.\n| nationality = \n| other_names = \n| known_for = \n| education = Wallace University Prep School\n| alma mater= [[Vanderbilt University]]\n| employer = \n| occupation = Businessman\n| title = \n| salary = \n| networth = $600,000 <small>(1934)</small><ref name=\"courierjournalcolewill\"/>\n| term = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| party = \n| boards = \n| religion = \n| spouse = Mary Conner Bass\n| children = 1\n| parents = [[Edmund William Cole]]<br/>Anna Russell\n| relatives = [[John Trotwood Moore]] <small>(daughter-in-law's father)</small>\n| box_width = \n}}\n'''Whiteford Russell Cole''' (January 14, 1874 \u2013 November 17, 1934) was an American businessman. He was the president of the [[Louisville and Nashville Railroad]] from 1926 to 1934, and a director of many companies. During the railroad [[strike action]]s of 1921\u20131922, he threatened his workers with dismissal and loss of pensions. His mansion in [[Louisville, Kentucky]] is the official residence of the president of the [[University of Louisville]].\n\n==Early life==\nWhiteford Russell Cole was born on January 14, 1874, in [[Nashville, Tennessee]].<ref name=\"stlouisdispatchobituary\">{{cite news|title=L. & N. PRESIDENT, W. R. COLE, DIES; STRICKEN ON TRAIN. On Way Home to Louisville After Consulting Doctor When End Comes\u201460 Years Old.|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/139037786/?terms=%22Whitefoord%2BRussell%2BCole%22|work=St. Louis Post-Dispatch|date=November 18, 1934|page=1|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url-access=registration }}</ref><ref name=\"tennesseanwillbeburied\">{{cite news|title=WHITEFORD COLE WILL BE BURIED IN NASHVILLE TODAY. Special Train to Bring Body for Service.|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/172725641/?terms=%22Whitefoord%2BR.%2BCole%22|accessdate=October 25, 2017|work=The Tennessean|date=November 19, 1934|pages=1; 3|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url-access=registration }}</ref><ref name=\"tennesseanwhitefoodchosen18\">{{cite news|title=WHITEFORD COLE CHOSEN TO HEAD N., C. & ST. L. R. R.. Local Capitalist Elected to Succeed John H. Peyton as President. SAME PLACE FILLED BY FATHER FIFTY YEARS AGO. T. R. Preston and Walker Keith Elected to Vacancies in Directorate.|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/119345349|accessdate=October 27, 2017|work=The Tennessean|date=October 9, 1918|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url-access=registration |pages=1; 10}}</ref> His father, [[Edmund William Cole]], was a Confederate veteran and railroad executive; his mother, Anna Russell, was a philanthropist.<ref name=\"tennesseanwhitefoodchosen18\"/><ref name=\"jstorannerussellcoleastudyof\">{{cite journal|last1=Burt|first1=Jesse C., Jr.|title=Anna Russell Cole: A Study of a Grande Dame|journal=Tennessee Historical Quarterly|date=June 1954|volume=13|issue=2|pages=127\u2013155|jstor=42621182}}</ref> His maternal uncle, Whitefoord Russell, was a Confederate veteran, and his maternal great-uncle was a professor at the [[University of Georgia]] and [[Berlin University]].<ref name=\"jstorannerussellcoleastudyof\"/> Cole grew up at [[Colemere]], a mansion in Nashville, with three half-siblings from his father's first marriage to a member of the McGavock family; his parents entertained often.<ref name=\"jstorannerussellcoleastudyof\"/>\n\nCole was educated at the Wallace University Prep School.<ref name=\"courierjournalheadofroad\">{{cite news|title=HEAD OF ROAD SUCCUMBS IN PRIVATE CAR. Business Leader Was Returning to Louisville From Nashville. CHIEF OF LINE 8 YEARS. Porter Stops Train, Calls Doctor, Who Finds Executive Dead.|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/107507237/?terms=%22Whitefoord%2BR.%2BCole%22|accessdate=October 25, 2017|work=The Courier-Journal|date=November 18, 1934|location=Louisville, Kentucky|page=2|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url-access=registration }}</ref> He graduated from [[Vanderbilt University]] in 1894.<ref name=\"tennesseanwhitefoodchosen18\"/><ref name=\"tnportrait\">{{cite web|title=Whitefoord Russell Cole 1874 \u2013 1934|url=http://tnportraits.org/cole-whitefoord-russell.htm|website=Tennessee Portrait Project|publisher=National Society of Colonial Dames of America in Tennessee|accessdate=October 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nCole was appointed as a director of the [[Nashville, Chattanooga and St. Louis Railway]] at the age of 26, in 1900.<ref name=\"stlouisdispatchobituary\"/> He had become its chairman by the outset of World War I,<ref name=\"stlouisdispatchobituary\"/> and he was appointed as its president in 1918.<ref name=\"filsonclubarticle\"/><ref name=\"tennesseanwhitefoodchosen18\"/> In 1919, he opposed [[Director General of Railroads]] [[William Gibbs McAdoo]]'s proposal to [[Nationalization|nationalize]] railroads for five years, arguing that \"debts would pile so high that it would be physically impossible for the roads to ever again revert to private ownership\".<ref name=\"rotariansopposed4\">{{cite news|title=ROTARIANS ARE OPPOSED TO U.S. RAIL CONTROL. Whitefoord Cole Says Debts Would Swamp Roads in Five-Year Period.|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/119394020/?terms=%22Whitefoord%2BCole%22|accessdate=October 27, 2017|work=The Tennesean|date=January 29, 1919|page=4|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url-access=registration }}</ref> In 1921\u20131922, when his railroad workers went on strike after their wages were lowered by 12 percent by the [[Railroad Labor Board|U.S. Railway Labor Board]], Cole threatened them with dismissal and loss of their pensions.<ref name=\"filsonclubarticle\"/><ref name=\"tennesseeanboardmeetsrailand\">{{cite news|title=BOARD MEETS RAIL AND \"BIG FIVE\" CHIEFS TODAY. Whitefoord R. Cole, President of N., C. & St. L., Appeals to Employees on His Road. Asks Men to Consider Situation Well Before Deciding to Walk Out on October 30.|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/118940592|accessdate=25 October 2017|work=The Tennessean|date=October 26, 1921|pages=1; 10|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url-access=registration }}</ref> In retaliation, strikers went to his house on West End Avenue, and they \"bombarded [it] with bottles until its concrete porch was littered with glass\".<ref name=\"filsonclubarticle\"/> In 1923, Cole dedicated the Whitefoord Cole Park in [[Murfreesboro, Tennessee]], for use by residents even though it belonged to the company.<ref name=\"tennesseanmurfreesboropark\">{{cite news|title=Murfreesboro Park Will Be Dedicated|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/178412876/?terms=%22Whitefoord%2BCole%22|accessdate=October 26, 2017|work=The Tennessean|date=July 24, 1923|page=2|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url-access=registration }}</ref> Cole resigned in 1926.<ref name=\"instepwith\">{{cite news|title=L. & N. HEAD IN STEP WITH SOUTH'S GROWTH. PRODUCTS SHOWS BIG INCREASE. Whitefoord R. Cole Cites Figures on Rail Shipments to Show Development. SOLD IN SOUTH. Rail Magnate Also Devotes Time To Vanderbilt University, Heading Board.|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/178891730/?terms=%22Whitefoord%2BR.%2BCole%22|accessdate=October 27, 2017|work=The Tennessean|date=October 30, 1927|page=35|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url-access=registration }}</ref>\n\nCole was the president of the [[Louisville and Nashville Railroad]] from 1926 to 1934.<ref name=\"instepwith\"/><ref name=\"stlouisdispatchobituary\"/><ref name=\"filsonclubarticle\">{{cite journal|last1=Burt|first1=Jesse C., Jr|title=Whitefoord Russell Cole: A Study in Character|journal=[[The Filson Club History Quarterly]]|date=January 1954|volume=28|pages=28\u201348}}</ref> At the time of his appointment, [[B. C. Forbes]], the founder of ''[[Forbes]]'' magazine, noted that it was unusual for a man of privileged upbringing to become the president of a railroad company.<ref name=\"philadelphiainquirerrichboyhaschance\">{{cite news|last1=Forbes|first1=B. C.|title=RICH BOY HAS CHANCE IN THE UNITED STATES. When He Buckles Down to Work With Determination to Win Wealth Is Not An Insurmountable Obstacle; New President of Louisville and Nashville Proves an Example|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/173520100/?terms=%22Whitefoord%2BR.%2BCole%22|work=The Philadelphia Inquirer|date=June 1, 1926|page=32|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url-access=registration }}</ref> As it was the [[Great Depression]], Cole lowered his workers' wages and took a pay cut.<ref name=\"filsonclubarticle\"/>\n\nCole was the president and general manager of the Napier Iron Works and vice president of the First Savings Bank & Trust Company and the Bransford Realty Company.<ref name=\"tennesseanwhitefoodchosen18\"/> He also served on the boards of directors of First and Fourth National Bank, Nashville Trust Company,<ref name=\"tennesseanwhitefoodchosen18\"/> the [[Western Railway of Alabama]],<ref name=\"stlouisdispatchobituary\"/> the [[Monon Railroad]], the Southern Bell Telephone & Telegraph Company, the American Nashville Bank of Nashville, [[American Cyanamid]], [[Fruit Growers Express]] and Fidelity & Columbia Trust Company.<ref name=\"courierjournalheadofroad\"/> He was a member of the [[Association of American Railroads]].<ref name=\"courierjournalheadofroad\"/>\n\nCole was a significant real estate investor in [[Sheffield, Alabama]].<ref name=\"thetennesseanonehundredhouses\">{{cite news|title=ONE HUNDRED HOUSES. Whitefoord Cole May Erect Them at Sheffield.|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/118842107/?terms=%22Whitefoord%2BCole%22|accessdate=October 27, 2017|work=The Tennessean|date=March 25, 1902|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url-access=registration |page=2}}</ref>\n\n==Civic activities and politics==\nCole served on the board of trustees of the [[Brookings Institution]].<ref name=\"stlouisdispatchobituary\"/> He served on the board of trustees of the Tennessee Industrial School, founded by his father, and the [[University School of Nashville]].<ref name=\"tennesseanwhitefoodchosen18\"/> He was also the chairman of the board of trust of his alma mater, Vanderbilt University, from 1915 to 1934.<ref name=\"tnportrait\"/> He supported chancellor [[James Hampton Kirkland]]'s decision to split with the [[Methodist Church]].<ref name=\"filsonclubarticle\"/> He served on the board of missions of the [[Methodist Episcopal Church, South]]<ref name=\"tennesseanwhitefoodchosen18\"/> until he joined the Episcopal Church, possibly as a return of the split.<ref name=\"filsonclubarticle\"/>\n\nCole was a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]].<ref name=\"rotariansopposed4\"/> According to ''[[The Tennessean]]'', he was opposed to \"any move that made for a greater centralization of governmental power than was necessary to perform its proper functions\".<ref name=\"rotariansopposed4\"/> He was a critic of [[laissez-faire capitalism]] as well as [[communism]].<ref name=\"filsonclubarticle\"/>\n\n==Personal life, death and legacy==\nCole married Mary Conner Bass, a direct descendant of [[Felix Grundy]], in 1901.<ref name=\"filsonclubarticle\"/> They had a son, Whitefoord Russell Cole, Jr.,<ref name=\"filsonclubarticle\"/> who married Helen Lane Moore, the daughter of State Historian and Archivist [[John Trotwood Moore]] and sister of poet [[Merrill Moore]].<ref name=\"courierjournalheadofroad\"/> They resided at 2122 West End Avenue, which was later repurposed as the Nashville Conservatory of Music.<ref name=\"tennesseanwillbeburied\"/> In 1926, they moved to 2515 Longest Avenue in [[Louisville, Kentucky]] (now known as Amelia Place, the official resident of the president of the [[University of Louisville]]).<ref name=\"tennesseanwillbeburied\"/><ref name=\"eventcalendarlouisville\">{{cite web|title=Event Calendar: Amelia Place|url=http://events.louisville.edu/amelia_place#.We_c9RNSzBI|website=University of Louisville|accessdate=October 25, 2017}}</ref> Cole was a member of the Nashville Golf and Country Club, the [[Pendennis Club]], the Louisville Country Club, and the [[Salmagundi Club]].<ref name=\"courierjournalheadofroad\"/>\n\nCole died of [[Cardiovascular disease|heart disease]] on November 17, 1934 on a train in [[Cave City, Kentucky]].<ref name=\"stlouisdispatchobituary\"/> He was 60 years old.<ref name=\"stlouisdispatchobituary\"/> His funeral was held at the [[Christ Church Cathedral (Nashville, Tennessee)|Christ Church Cathedral]],<ref name=\"tennesseanwillbeburied\"/> and he was buried in Nashville.<ref name=\"courierjournalheadofroad\"/> By the time of his death, he was worth an estimated $600,000.<ref name=\"courierjournalcolewill\">{{cite news|title=COLE WILL DISPOSES OF $600,000 ESTATE|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/107507767/?terms=%22Whitefoord%2BR.%2BCole%22|accessdate=October 25, 2017|work=The Courier-Journal|date=November 27, 1934|location=Louisville, Kentucky|page=4|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url-access=registration }}</ref> His estate was split between his wife and his son (whose trust fund would become available at age 30).<ref name=\"courierjournalcolewill\"/> Cole also bequeathed money to the Christ Church cathedrals in Nashville and [[Christ Church Cathedral (Louisville, Kentucky)|Louisville]].<ref name=\"courierjournalcolewill\"/>\n\nCole Hall, a building on the Vanderbilt campus completed in 1949, was named in his honor.<ref name=\"tnportrait\"/> Additionally, his portrait hangs in Kirkland Hall, the administration building;<ref name=\"tnportrait\"/> it was donated by his son in 1958.<ref name=\"portraitgiven\">{{cite news|title=Whitefood Cole, Sr., Portrait Given by Son to Vanderbilt|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/107767686/?terms=%22Whitefoord%2BRussell%2BCole%22|work=The Courier-Journal|date=January 16, 1958|location=Louisville, Kentucky|page=15|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|url-access=registration }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cole, Whitefoord Russell}}\n[[Category:1874 births]]\n[[Category:1934 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Nashville, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:People from Louisville, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Vanderbilt University alumni]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Kentucky]]\n[[Category:American corporate directors]]\n[[Category:University of Louisville people]]\n[[Category:Louisville and Nashville Railroad people]]\n[[Category:Kentucky Democrats]]\n[[Category:Tennessee Democrats]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer:Typo fixing, replaced: Tennesean \u2192 Tennessean", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Whitefoord_Russell_Cole"}
